// Unit 9: Freizeit und Vereine
// Level: A2

const UNIT_9 =
{n:9,lang:"de",srcLang:"en",track:"v2",title:"Freizeit und Vereine",sub:"Running club, Vereinskultur, hobbies, and German social life",icon:"🏃",level:"A2.2",color:"#7B5EE8",lessons:[
// ─── L1: Der Lauftreff ───
{id:"deu_r9l1",title:"Der Lauftreff",icon:"🏃",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Der Lauftreff",desc:"Mia drags Verumius to her running club in Volkspark Friedrichshain. It's 6:30 AM, the autumn air bites, and Verumius is already regretting this.",goals:["Learn 12 sports and leisure words","Discover German Vereinskultur","Survive your first Lauftreff"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Ball", pos:"noun", gender:"m",src:"the ball",note:"Masculine noun. Plural: die Bälle.",example:"A: Hast du einen Ball?\nB: Ja, der Ball ist im Auto.\nA: Dann hol ihn schnell!",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a ball?\nB: Yes, the ball is in the car.\nA: Then go get it quickly!",funFact:"'Ball' is identical in English and German. It comes from Old High German 'bal.' Germans host over 400 'Bälle' (formal dance balls) each year, most famously the Vienna Opera Ball."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Fan", pos:"noun", gender:"m",src:"the fan (supporter)",note:"Masculine noun. Plural: die Fans. Borrowed from English.",example:"A: Bist du ein Fan von Bayern München?\nB: Nein! Ich bin ein Fan von Dortmund!\nA: Oh, dann können wir nicht Freunde sein.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you a fan of Bayern Munich?\nB: No! I'm a fan of Dortmund!\nA: Oh, then we can't be friends.",funFact:"Germany's Bundesliga has the highest average stadium attendance in the world. Borussia Dortmund's 'Gelbe Wand' (Yellow Wall) holds 25,000 standing fans in one section alone."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Mannschaft", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"the team",note:"Feminine noun. Plural: die Mannschaften.",example:"A: Welche Mannschaft spielt heute?\nB: Die Mannschaft aus Berlin spielt gegen Hamburg.\nA: Das wird ein gutes Spiel!",exampleSrc:"A: Which team is playing today?\nB: The team from Berlin is playing against Hamburg.\nA: That will be a good game!",funFact:"The German national football team is simply called 'die Mannschaft' (the team). The word comes from 'Mann' (man) + '-schaft' (collective suffix), like English '-ship' in 'fellowship.'"},
{type:"fb",s:"Bist du ein {1} von Bayern München?",a:["Fan"],opts:["Fan","Ball","Mannschaft","Spiel"],hint:"Which borrowed English word means a supporter of a team?",sSrc:"Are you a fan of Bayern Munich?"},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Sportplatz", pos:"noun", gender:"m",src:"the sports field",note:"Masculine compound noun: Sport + Platz (place).",example:"A: Wo ist der Sportplatz?\nB: Der Sportplatz ist hinter der Schule.\nA: Danke! Wir trainieren dort um vier.",exampleSrc:"A: Where is the sports field?\nB: The sports field is behind the school.\nA: Thanks! We train there at four.",funFact:"Every German neighborhood has a Sportplatz. There are over 90,000 sports facilities in Germany. Even tiny villages have their own football field with a clubhouse."},
{type:"mc",q:"Mia says 'Die Mannschaft trainiert auf dem Sportplatz.' Where does the team train?",opts:["On the sports field","At the train station","In the swimming pool","At the supermarket"],ans:"On the sports field",hint:"'Sportplatz' is a compound of Sport and a word meaning 'place.'"},
{type:"fb",s:"Bist du ein {1} von Dortmund?",a:["Fan"],opts:["Fan","Ball","Spiel","Mannschaft"],hint:"Which borrowed English word means a supporter of a team?",sSrc:"Are you a fan of Dortmund?"},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Training", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"the training / practice",note:"Neuter noun. No common plural form in everyday use.",example:"A: Wann ist das Training?\nB: Das Training ist um sechs Uhr.\nA: So früh? Das ist hart!",exampleSrc:"A: When is the training?\nB: The training is at six o'clock.\nA: So early? That's tough!",funFact:"Germans take training schedules seriously. Club training sessions run year-round, rain or shine. The phrase 'Übung macht den Meister' (practice makes the master) is a national motto."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Spiel", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"the game / match",note:"Neuter noun. Plural: die Spiele.",example:"A: Wie war das Spiel?\nB: Das Spiel war fantastisch! 3:1 für uns.\nA: Toll! Wer hat die Tore geschossen?",exampleSrc:"A: How was the game?\nB: The game was fantastic! 3-1 for us.\nA: Great! Who scored the goals?",funFact:"'Spiel' gives us 'Spielplatz' (playground), 'Spielzeug' (toy, literally play-stuff), and the verb 'spielen.' Steven Spielberg's surname literally means 'play mountain.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Spaziergang", pos:"noun", gender:"m",src:"the walk / stroll",note:"Masculine compound: spazieren (to stroll) + Gang (way/path).",example:"A: Machen wir einen Spaziergang?\nB: Ja, gerne! Im Park?\nA: Perfekt. Die Sonne scheint.",exampleSrc:"A: Shall we go for a walk?\nB: Yes, I'd love to! In the park?\nA: Perfect. The sun is shining.",funFact:"The Sunday 'Spaziergang' is a sacred German tradition. After lunch, families walk through parks or forests. It is considered healthy, social, and deeply German. Some call it 'Verdauungsspaziergang' (digestion walk)."},
{type:"mc",q:"Verumius says 'Machen wir einen Spaziergang im Park?' What is he suggesting?",opts:["Let's eat in the park","Let's go for a walk in the park","Let's play a game in the park","Let's train in the park"],ans:"Let's go for a walk in the park",hint:"A 'Spaziergang' is a relaxed, leisurely outdoor activity."}]},
{id:"deu_r9l1b",title:"Der Lauftreff (Teil 2)",icon:"🏃",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Der Lauftreff (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"joggen", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to jog",note:"Borrowed from English. Regular: ich jogge, du joggst.",example:"A: Gehst du gerne joggen?\nB: Ja, ich jogge jeden Morgen im Park.\nA: Alleine oder mit Freunden?",exampleSrc:"A: Do you like jogging?\nB: Yes, I jog every morning in the park.\nA: Alone or with friends?",funFact:"Germans borrowed 'joggen' in the 1970s running boom. They even created 'der Jogger' and 'die Joggerin.' English sports words flood German: 'der Sprint,' 'das Workout,' 'das Stretching.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"trainieren", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to train / to work out",note:"Regular: ich trainiere, du trainierst, er trainiert.",example:"A: Wie oft trainierst du?\nB: Ich trainiere dreimal pro Woche.\nA: Das ist beeindruckend!",exampleSrc:"A: How often do you train?\nB: I train three times per week.\nA: That's impressive!",funFact:"From Latin 'trahere' (to pull/drag), through French 'trainer.' The same root gave English 'train' (the vehicle literally pulls carriages). In German, 'trainieren' is ONLY for exercise, never for vehicles."},
{type:"teach",trg:"spazieren", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to walk / to stroll",note:"Regular: ich spaziere, du spazierst. Often used with 'gehen.'",example:"A: Was machst du am Sonntag?\nB: Ich gehe spazieren. Kommst du mit?\nA: Klar! Wohin gehen wir?",exampleSrc:"A: What are you doing on Sunday?\nB: I'm going for a walk. Do you want to come?\nA: Sure! Where are we going?",funFact:"'Spazieren' comes from Italian 'spaziare' (to wander). It arrived in German during the Renaissance when Italian culture was fashionable. A walk borrowed from Italy!"},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich {1} jeden Morgen im Park.",a:["jogge"],opts:["jogge","spaziere","trainiere","spiele"],hint:"Which verb specifically means running at a moderate pace?",sSrc:"I jog every morning in the park."},
{type:"teach",trg:"aktiv", pos:"adj", gender:null,src:"active",note:"Same spelling as English. Used with sein: 'Ich bin aktiv.'",example:"A: Bist du sportlich?\nB: Ja, ich bin sehr aktiv. Ich jogge und schwimme.\nA: Respekt!",exampleSrc:"A: Are you sporty?\nB: Yes, I'm very active. I jog and swim.\nA: Respect!",funFact:"Germany ranks among the most physically active countries in Europe. Over 27 million Germans are members of a sports club. That is one in three people!"},
{type:"teach",trg:"sportlich", pos:"adj", gender:null,src:"sporty / athletic",note:"From 'Sport' + '-lich' (similar to English '-ly'). Used for people AND things.",example:"A: Mia ist wirklich sportlich!\nB: Ja, sie trainiert jeden Tag.\nA: Ich bin leider nicht so sportlich.",exampleSrc:"A: Mia is really sporty!\nB: Yes, she trains every day.\nA: Unfortunately I'm not that sporty.",funFact:"The suffix '-lich' turns nouns into adjectives: Sport to sportlich, Freund to freundlich, Herz to herzlich. Once you know this trick, you can decode hundreds of German adjectives."},
{type:"mc",q:"Verumius says 'Mia ist sportlich, ich bin es nicht.' What does 'sportlich' mean?",opts:["Tired","Hungry","Sporty","Late"],ans:"Sporty",hint:"This adjective is built from a word you already know plus '-lich.'"},
{type:"tip",title:"Vereinskultur: The Heart of German Community",text:"Germany has over 600,000 registered Vereine (clubs).\n\nFootball clubs, hiking clubs, running clubs, singing clubs, rabbit-breeding clubs.\n\n'Sich treffen' (to meet up) and 'sich anmelden' (to register) are key verbs for club life. You will learn these soon!\n\nJoining a Verein is how Germans build community. Mia's Lauftreff is a perfect example: same people, same time, same park, every week.",deepDive:"The first German Verein was founded in 1791. Today, about 44% of all Germans belong to at least one club. The concept is so central to German identity that 'Vereinsmeier' (someone obsessed with club rules) is a well-known word. Many clubs have a 'Stammtisch' (regulars' table) at a local pub where members meet after activities."},
{type:"mc",q:"How many registered Vereine (clubs) does Germany have?",opts:["About 6,000","About 60,000","About 6,000,000","About 600,000"],ans:"About 600,000",hint:"The tip card gave you a statistic. It is between 500,000 and 700,000."},
{type:"fb",s:"Mia ist sehr {1}. Sie trainiert jeden Tag.",a:["sportlich"],opts:["sportlich","aktiv","müde","hungrig"],hint:"Which adjective describes someone who is athletic?",sSrc:"Mia is very sporty. She trains every day."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"der Ball", pos:"noun", gender:"m",src:"the ball"},{trg:"die Mannschaft", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"the team"},{trg:"das Spiel", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"the game"},{trg:"joggen", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to jog"},{trg:"trainieren", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to train"},{trg:"spazieren", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to stroll"},{trg:"aktiv", pos:"adj", gender:null,src:"active"},{trg:"sportlich", pos:"adj", gender:null,src:"sporty"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"'Das Training macht dich fit.' What does 'das Training' mean?",opts:["The training","The game (different meaning)","The walk","The team"],ans:"The training",hint:"This neuter noun describes the activity of practicing a sport."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Mia ist {1} und {2}. Sie geht jeden Samstag zum {3}.",blanks:{"1":"aktiv","2":"sportlich","3":"Lauftreff"},pool:["aktiv","sportlich","Lauftreff","müde","Spiel"],hint:"Describe Mia's character and her Saturday activity.",sSrc:"Mia is active and sporty. She goes every Saturday to the Lauftreff."}
]}
,

{id:"deu_r9l2",title:"Was machst du gern?",icon:"🎨",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Was machst du gern?",desc:"Learn words for hobbies, art, and culture.",goals:["14 new words for leisure and culture","Talk about hobbies and interests","Describe cultural venues and activities"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Musik", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"music",note:"Feminine. Music plays a huge role in Germany.",funFact:"Germany has over 130 professional orchestras, more than any other country in the world.",example:"A: Hörst du gern Musik?\nB: Ja, ich höre jeden Tag Musik.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you like listening to music?\nB: Yes, I listen to music every day."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Instrument", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"instrument",note:"Neuter. Plural: die Instrumente.",funFact:"About 18% of Germans play an instrument. Piano and guitar are the most popular.",example:"A: Spielst du ein Instrument?\nB: Ja, ich spiele seit drei Jahren.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you play an instrument?\nB: Yes, I have been playing for three years."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Gitarre", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"guitar",note:"Feminine. Plural: die Gitarren.",funFact:"The classical guitar arrived in Germany in the 19th century and quickly became popular in youth hiking groups.",example:"A: Kannst du Gitarre spielen?\nB: Ein bisschen. Ich lerne noch.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you play guitar?\nB: A little. I am still learning."},
{type:"mc",q:"Welches Instrument hat sechs Saiten?",opts:["Das Klavier","Die Gitarre","Die Trompete","Die Flöte"],ans:"Die Gitarre",hint:"This string instrument is popular in rock, pop, and classical music."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Klavier", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"piano",note:"Neuter. Plural: die Klaviere. The word comes from Latin clavis (key).",funFact:"Beethoven, Bach, Brahms. Germany has produced more famous piano composers than almost any other country.",example:"A: Mein Sohn spielt Klavier.\nB: Toll! Seit wann?\nA: Seit September.",exampleSrc:"A: My son plays piano.\nB: Great! Since when?\nA: Since September."},
{type:"mc",q:"Wie sagt man 'guitar' auf Deutsch?",opts:["die Gitarre","das Klavier","die Musik","das Instrument"],ans:"die Gitarre",hint:"A string instrument with six strings."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Kunst", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"art",note:"Feminine. Kein Plural in dieser Bedeutung.",funFact:"The documenta in Kassel is one of the world's most important art exhibitions. It takes place every five years.",example:"A: Interessierst du dich für Kunst?\nB: Ja, besonders für moderne Kunst.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you interested in art?\nB: Yes, especially modern art."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Kultur", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"culture",note:"Feminine. Kulturell is the adjective form.",funFact:"Many German cities offer a Kulturkarte (culture card) with discounts for museums, theaters, and concerts.",example:"A: Die Kultur hier ist sehr interessant.\nB: Ja, es gibt so viel zu sehen!",exampleSrc:"A: The culture here is very interesting.\nB: Yes, there is so much to see!"},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Museum", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"museum",note:"Neuter. Plural: die Museen (nicht Museums!).",funFact:"Berlin's Museum Island holds five museums and is a UNESCO World Heritage Site.",example:"A: Warst du schon im Museum?\nB: Ja, das Pergamonmuseum ist fantastisch.",exampleSrc:"A: Have you been to the museum?\nB: Yes, the Pergamon Museum is fantastic."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Ausstellung", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"exhibition",note:"Feminine. Plural: die Ausstellungen. Aus + Stellung = something is exhibited.",funFact:"Many German museums offer free entry on the first Sunday of each month.",example:"A: Gehst du in die Ausstellung?\nB: Ja, sie ist nur noch bis Freitag.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you going to the exhibition?\nB: Yes, it is only open until Friday."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich möchte ins {1} gehen. Die Ausstellung über Picasso beginnt heute.",a:["Museum"],opts:["Museum","Theater","Konzert","Bibliothek"],hint:"A place where you visit exhibitions.",sSrc:"I would like to go to the museum. The Picasso exhibition starts today."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Theater", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"theater",note:"Neuter. Plural: die Theater. Ins Theater gehen = to go to the theater.",funFact:"Germany has over 800 theatres, more per capita than any other country.",example:"A: Gehen wir am Samstag ins Theater?\nB: Gute Idee! Was wird gespielt?",exampleSrc:"A: Shall we go to the theater on Saturday?\nB: Good idea! What is playing?"},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Konzert", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"concert",note:"Neuter. Plural: die Konzerte. Ins Konzert gehen.",funFact:"The Elbphilharmonie in Hamburg has one of the best acoustics in the world. Tickets often sell out months in advance.",example:"A: Das Konzert war wunderbar!\nB: Ja, die Musik war so schön.",exampleSrc:"A: The concert was wonderful!\nB: Yes, the music was so beautiful."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Bibliothek", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"library",note:"Feminine. Plural: die Bibliotheken. Do not confuse with Buchhandlung (bookshop).",funFact:"The Deutsche Nationalbibliothek in Leipzig and Frankfurt collects every book published in German.",example:"A: Wo ist die Bibliothek?\nB: Gleich neben dem Museum.",exampleSrc:"A: Where is the library?\nB: Right next to the museum."},
{type:"mc",q:"Wo kann man Bücher lesen und ausleihen?",opts:["in der Bibliothek","im großen Museum","im alten Rathaus","im neuen Zentrum"],ans:"in der Bibliothek",hint:"This place is full of books and shelves."},
{type:"teach",trg:"malen", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to paint",note:"Regular: ich male, du malst, er malt.",funFact:"Gerhard Richter is one of the most expensive living painters in the world. He comes from Dresden.",example:"A: Was machst du am Wochenende?\nB: Ich male ein Bild für meine Mutter.",exampleSrc:"A: What are you doing on the weekend?\nB: I am painting a picture for my mother."},
{type:"teach",trg:"zeichnen", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to draw",note:"Regular verb: ich zeichne, du zeichnest, er zeichnet. Used with pencil or charcoal.",funFact:"Albrecht Dürer from Nuremberg was one of the greatest draughtsmen of all time. His painting of a hare is world-famous.",example:"A: Kannst du gut zeichnen?\nB: Es geht. Ich zeichne gern Tiere.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you draw well?\nB: So-so. I like drawing animals."},
{type:"teach",trg:"basteln", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to do crafts",note:"Regular verb: ich bastle, du bastelst. Basteln means making things creatively by hand.",funFact:"Crafting (Basteln) is a serious hobby in Germany. There are entire shops dedicated solely to craft supplies.",example:"A: Die Kinder basteln Laternen für Sankt Martin.\nB: Oh, wie schön! Aus Papier?",exampleSrc:"A: The children are making lanterns for St. Martin's Day.\nB: Oh, how nice! Out of paper?"},
{type:"tip",title:"Musikvereine und Kulturvereine",text:"Germany has thousands of clubs for music and culture.\n\n- Musikverein: members play together in an orchestra or band.\n- Kulturverein: members organize exhibitions, readings, or theater evenings.\n- Volkshochschule (VHS): here you can learn to paint, draw, or do crafts.\n\nA club often costs just 5 to 15 euros a month. Almost every village has a Musikverein!",deepDive:"German club culture (Vereinswesen) has roots going back to the 19th century. Today there are around 600,000 registered associations (e.V.) in Germany. Many children learn their first instrument through a Musikverein."},
{type:"mc",q:"Lena spielt gern Klavier und Gitarre. Was spielt sie?",opts:["Ausstellungen","Theater","Instrumente","Kultur"],ans:"Instrumente",hint:"A word for things that make music."},
{type:"fb",s:"Am Samstag gehen wir ins {1}. Wir sehen ein Stück von Schiller.",a:["Theater"],opts:["Theater","Museum","Konzert","Bibliothek"],hint:"A place where actors perform on stage.",sSrc:"On Saturday we are going to the theater. We are seeing a play by Schiller."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Mein Bruder {1} gern und meine Schwester {2} gern. Beide lieben {3}.",blanks:{"1":"malt","2":"zeichnet","3":"Kunst"},pool:["malt","zeichnet","Kunst","bastelt","Musik","Kultur"],hint:"He uses paints, she uses pencil, both love it.",sSrc:"My brother paints and my sister draws. Both love art."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"die Ausstellung", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"exhibition"},{trg:"das Konzert", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"concert"},{trg:"die Bibliothek", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"library"},{trg:"basteln", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to do crafts"},{trg:"zeichnen", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to draw"},{trg:"die Gitarre", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"guitar"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"Was macht man in einer Bibliothek?",opts:["Konzerte besuchen","Bilder malen","Bücher lesen und ausleihen","Instrumente spielen"],ans:"Bücher lesen und ausleihen",hint:"Think of shelves, silence, and a card you borrow with."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich gehe heute Abend ins {1}. Die Band spielt meine Lieblingsmusik!",a:["Konzert"],opts:["Konzert","Museum","Theater","Bibliothek"],hint:"An event where a band plays music live.",sSrc:"I am going to the concert tonight. The band is playing my favorite music!"}]},

// ─── L3: Die Vereinssitzung ───
{id:"deu_r9l3",title:"Die Vereinssitzung",icon:"📋",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Die Vereinssitzung",desc:"Verumius attends his first Verein meeting. Folding chairs, a whiteboard, and a binder labeled SATZUNG. Mia runs a surprisingly formal meeting for a running club.",goals:["Learn reflexive verbs with accusative pronouns","Understand dass-clauses with verb-final word order","Talk about events, fun, and participation"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Interesse", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"the interest",note:"Neuter noun. Plural: die Interessen. 'Interesse an + Dativ.'",example:"A: Hast du Interesse an dem Laufverein?\nB: Ja, ich habe großes Interesse!",exampleSrc:"A: Are you interested in the running club?\nB: Yes, I have great interest!",funFact:"Borrowed directly from Latin 'interesse' (to be between). German, French, English, and Italian all use the same word. A true European traveler."},
{type:"teach",trg:"sich interessieren",src:"to be interested in",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Reflexive verb. Ich interessiere mich f\u00fcr + accusative.",example:"A: Wof\u00fcr interessierst du dich?\nB: Ich interessiere mich f\u00fcr Musik und Sport.\nA: Interessierst du dich auch f\u00fcr Kunst?\nB: Ja, besonders f\u00fcr moderne Kunst.",exampleSrc:"A: What are you interested in?\nB: I am interested in music and sport.\nA: Are you also interested in art?\nB: Yes, especially modern art.",funFact:"'Sich interessieren f\u00fcr' always takes the accusative. Many German emotion and attitude verbs use reflexive 'sich': sich freuen (to be happy), sich \u00e4rgern (to be annoyed), sich interessieren (to be interested)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Lust", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"the desire / mood (to do something)",note:"Feminine noun. 'Hast du Lust?' = Do you feel like it?",example:"A: Hast du Lust auf ein Bier nach dem Training?\nB: Ja, ich habe total Lust!",exampleSrc:"A: Do you feel like a beer after training?\nB: Yes, I totally feel like it!",funFact:"'Hast du Lust?' is how Germans casually invite people to do things. It is warmer than 'Möchtest du?' and more natural in everyday speech. You will hear it constantly."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich habe {1} auf einen Film heute Abend.",a:["Lust"],opts:["Lust","Spaß","Interesse","Fest"],hint:"Which noun expresses wanting to do something fun?",sSrc:"I feel like watching a movie tonight."},
{type:"mc",q:"Er interessiert sich für Musik. Was bedeutet 'sich interessieren für'?",opts:["to feel bored and tired by","to be interested in","to be afraid of","to be angry at"],ans:"to be interested in",hint:"The reflexive verb describes a personal curiosity or attraction."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Spaß", pos:"noun", gender:"m",src:"the fun",note:"Masculine noun. 'Das macht Spaß!' = That is fun!",example:"A: Macht Laufen Spaß?\nB: Ja, das macht total Spaß!",exampleSrc:"A: Is running fun?\nB: Yes, it is totally fun!",funFact:"Both 'Spaß machen' (to make fun) and 'Spaß haben' (to have fun) are common in German. 'Das macht Spaß!' focuses on the activity creating fun. 'Ich habe Spaß!' focuses on your experience. You will hear both all the time."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Fest", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"the celebration / festival",note:"Neuter noun. Plural: die Feste. Think: Oktoberfest!",example:"A: Wann ist das Sommerfest?\nB: Das Fest ist im Juli.",exampleSrc:"A: When is the summer festival?\nB: The festival is in July.",funFact:"'Fest' gives us Oktoberfest, Weinfest, Schützenfest, Volksfest. Germany has over 10,000 festivals per year. If there is a reason to celebrate, there is a Fest for it."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Feier", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"the party / celebration",note:"Feminine noun. Plural: die Feiern. More personal than Fest.",example:"A: Kommst du zur Feier am Samstag?\nB: Ja, ich komme gerne zur Feier!",exampleSrc:"A: Are you coming to the party on Saturday?\nB: Yes, I'd love to come to the party!",funFact:"'Feier' is for personal celebrations (birthdays, weddings). 'Fest' is for public ones (festivals, fairs). A birthday is a Feier, not a Fest. Oktoberfest is a Fest, not a Feier."},
{type:"mc",q:"Wir haben ein großes Fest im Park. Alle tanzen und feiern. Was ist ein 'Fest'?",opts:["A formal written test","A festival or celebration","A fast train","A factory"],ans:"A festival or celebration",hint:"Think of joyful gatherings with music and dancing."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Veranstaltung", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"the event / organized occasion",note:"Feminine noun. Plural: die Veranstaltungen. Formal word.",example:"A: Welche Veranstaltungen gibt es im Mai?\nB: Es gibt drei Veranstaltungen im Mai.",exampleSrc:"A: Which events are there in May?\nB: There are three events in May.",funFact:"16 letters! One of those long German words that sounds scary but breaks down simply: ver + an + stalt + ung. 'Anstalt' means institution, 'ver-' makes it into an action. An organized occasion."},
{type:"mc",q:"Mia says 'Hast du Lust auf eine Feier?' What is she asking?",opts:["Do you have time for a party?","Do you need a party?","Do you feel like a party?","Do you know about a party?"],ans:"Do you feel like a party?",hint:"The phrase 'Lust haben auf' expresses desire or inclination. Think about how 'Lust' relates to enthusiasm."},
{type:"fb",s:"Das Training macht {1}!",a:["Spaß"],opts:["Spaß","Lust","Fest","Interesse"],hint:"Which masculine noun means 'fun' and pairs with 'machen'?",sSrc:"Training is fun!"},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Wettbewerb", pos:"noun", gender:"m",src:"the competition",note:"Masculine noun. Plural: die Wettbewerbe. Compound: Wette + Bewerb.",example:"A: Gibt es einen Wettbewerb im Oktober?\nB: Ja, der Wettbewerb ist am 15. Oktober.",exampleSrc:"A: Is there a competition in October?\nB: Yes, the competition is on October 15th.",funFact:"'Wette' means bet, 'Bewerb' comes from 'bewerben' (to apply/compete). A competition is literally a 'bet-application.' Germans once settled disputes by betting on athletic contests."},
{type:"teach",trg:"sich freuen", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to be happy / to look forward to",note:"Reflexive verb. 'Ich freue mich.' 'sich freuen auf' = look forward to.",example:"A: Ich freue mich auf das Fest!\nB: Ich freue mich auch!",exampleSrc:"A: I'm looking forward to the festival!\nB: I'm looking forward to it too!",funFact:"'Sich freuen' needs a reflexive pronoun. Without it, 'freuen' alone sounds wrong. The 'sich' is like saying 'to glad oneself.' German emotions often work this way: you do the feeling TO yourself."},
{type:"tip",title:"auf vs über with sich freuen",text:"The preposition changes the TIME direction:\n\nsich freuen AUF = looking FORWARD to something (future)\nIch freue mich auf die Ferien.\n\nsich freuen ÜBER = being happy ABOUT something (past or current)\nIch freue mich über das Ergebnis.\n\nauf = arrow pointing to the future. über = reflecting on what happened.",deepDive:{title:"darauf and darüber",text:"When a preposition refers to a thing (not a person), German uses da-compounds:\nFreust du dich auf den Urlaub? Ja, ich freue mich darauf.\nda + auf = darauf. da + über = darüber. You will study these fully in B1."}},
{type:"teach",trg:"sich treffen", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to meet up",note:"Reflexive + irregular: ich treffe mich, du triffst dich, er trifft sich.",example:"A: Wann treffen wir uns?\nB: Wir treffen uns um 18 Uhr.",exampleSrc:"A: When do we meet up?\nB: We meet up at 6 PM.",funFact:"'Treffen' alone means 'to hit' (a target). Add 'sich' and it becomes 'to meet.' The reflexive changes the entire meaning. You are not hitting anyone, you are meeting each other!"},
{type:"tip",title:"Reflexive Verbs: The 'sich' System",text:"Some German verbs need a reflexive pronoun. The pronoun refers back to the subject.\n\nThe reflexive pronoun sits between the subject and the rest of the sentence:\n- Ich freue mich. (I am happy.)\n- Du freust dich. (You are happy.)\n- Wir treffen uns. (We meet up.)\n\nThe reflexive pronoun changes with the subject. Next, you will see the full table.",deepDive:{title:"Accusative vs dative reflexive pronouns",text:"German has TWO sets of reflexive pronouns. The accusative set (mich, dich, sich, uns, euch, sich) is used when the reflexive pronoun is the DIRECT OBJECT of the verb.\n\nThe dative set (mir, dir, sich, uns, euch, sich) is used when the verb already has a direct object and the reflexive is the INDIRECT object.\n\nExample: Ich wasche mir die Hände. (I wash my hands, literally: I wash for-myself the hands.)\n\nNotice that uns, euch, and sich are the same in both sets. Only ich and du differ: mich/mir and dich/dir."}},
{type:"verb_table",title:"Accusative Reflexive Pronouns",groups:[{label:"Subject + reflexive pronoun",rows:[{pronoun:"ich",form:"mich",src:"myself"},{pronoun:"du",form:"dich",src:"yourself"},{pronoun:"er/sie/es",form:"sich",src:"himself/herself/itself"},{pronoun:"wir",form:"uns",src:"ourselves"},{pronoun:"ihr",form:"euch",src:"yourselves"},{pronoun:"sie/Sie",form:"sich",src:"themselves/yourself (formal)"}]},{label:"sich freuen (to be happy)",rows:[{pronoun:"ich",form:"freue mich",src:"I am happy"},{pronoun:"du",form:"freust dich",src:"you are happy"},{pronoun:"er/sie/es",form:"freut sich",src:"he/she/it is happy"},{pronoun:"wir",form:"freuen uns",src:"we are happy"},{pronoun:"ihr",form:"freut euch",src:"you all are happy"},{pronoun:"sie/Sie",form:"freuen sich",src:"they are / you (formal) are happy"}]}],note:"The reflexive pronoun sits right after the conjugated verb. In questions: 'Freust du dich?' Common reflexive verbs: sich freuen, sich treffen, sich anmelden, sich fühlen."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Ich freue mich auf das Fest.' What does 'mich' do in this sentence?",opts:["It means 'me' as a direct object","It means 'my' as a possessive","It replaces a noun that was mentioned before (alternative)","It is a reflexive pronoun referring back to 'ich'"],ans:"It is a reflexive pronoun referring back to 'ich'",hint:"In this special category, the same person both performs and undergoes the action. What role does that word play?"},
{type:"fb",s:"Wir treffen {1} um 18 Uhr im Park.",a:["uns"],opts:["uns","sich","mich","euch"],hint:"Which reflexive pronoun matches the subject 'wir'?",sSrc:"We meet up at 6 PM in the park."},
{type:"mc",q:"He is happy about the competition. What reflexive pronoun matches the 'er' form?",opts:["sich","mich","dich","uns"],ans:"sich",hint:"Third person (er, sie, es) always uses the same reflexive pronoun."},
{type:"fb",s:"Freust du {1} auf die Feier?",a:["dich"],opts:["dich","mich","sich","uns"],hint:"Which reflexive pronoun matches the subject 'du'?",sSrc:"Are you looking forward to the party?"}
]},

// ─── Lesson: Mitmachen und Planen ───
{id:"deu_r9l4",title:"Mitmachen und Planen",icon:"📋",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Mitmachen und Planen",desc:"Participate, organize, and plan events with dass-clauses. The meeting continues as Mia assigns tasks and Verumius discovers that German clubs run like small governments.",goals:["Learn verbs for participation and organization","Master dass-clauses with verb-final word order","Describe plans and beliefs using subordinate clauses"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"teilnehmen", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to participate / to take part",note:"Separable: ich nehme teil. 'An + Dativ' follows: 'am Wettbewerb teilnehmen.'",example:"A: Nimmst du am Wettbewerb teil?\nB: Ja, ich nehme teil!",exampleSrc:"A: Are you participating in the competition?\nB: Yes, I'm participating!",funFact:"'Teil' (part) + 'nehmen' (to take). Literally 'to take part.' English and German use the exact same logic here, word for word. Separable verbs split apart in main clauses: 'Ich nehme teil.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"stattfinden", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to take place / to happen",note:"Separable: es findet statt. 'Das Fest findet am Samstag statt.'",example:"A: Wann findet das Fest statt?\nB: Es findet am Samstag statt.",exampleSrc:"A: When does the festival take place?\nB: It takes place on Saturday.",funFact:"'Statt' (place/instead) + 'finden' (to find). An event 'finds its place.' This verb is almost always used with events and is very common in formal announcements and newspapers."},
{type:"teach",trg:"organisieren", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to organize",note:"Regular verb: ich organisiere, du organisierst, er organisiert.",example:"A: Wer organisiert das Sommerfest?\nB: Mia organisiert alles!",exampleSrc:"A: Who is organizing the summer festival?\nB: Mia organizes everything!",funFact:"Borrowed from French 'organiser.' German happily borrows words from French for anything cultural, administrative, or fashionable. Organisieren, reservieren, telefonieren: the -ieren ending is always French-origin."},
{type:"tip",title:"dass-Clauses: Verb Goes to the End",text:"After 'dass' (that), the conjugated verb moves to the END of the clause.\n\nMain clause: Ich glaube + dass-clause: dass wir ein Fest organisieren.\n\nIch glaube, dass wir ein Fest organisieren.\nEr sagt, dass das Fest am Samstag stattfindet.\nWir wissen, dass Mia alles organisiert.\n\nCommon starters: glauben (believe), sagen (say), wissen (know), denken (think), hoffen (hope).\n\nThe comma before 'dass' is mandatory in German.",deepDive:{title:"The four verb-final triggers",text:"'dass' is not the only conjunction that sends the verb to the end. Four key conjunctions follow the same rule:\n\nweil = because (reason)\ndass = that (thought/report)\nwenn = if/when (condition/habit)\nob = whether (indirect question)\n\nAll follow the same pattern: conjunction + subject + ... + VERB at the end.\n\nOther subordinating conjunctions you will meet later (obwohl, als, bevor, nachdem, seitdem, damit) all follow this same verb-final rule. Learning it now builds the habit for all subordinate clauses."}},
{type:"mc",q:"'Ich glaube, dass das Fest am Samstag stattfindet.' Where is the verb in the dass-clause?",opts:["Right after the word dass","In the second position","At the end of the clause","Before the comma itself"],ans:"At the end of the clause",hint:"Subordinating conjunctions push the finite form out of position 2 to the final spot."},
{type:"fb",s:"Er sagt, dass er sich auf die Veranstaltung {1}.",a:["freut"],opts:["freut","freuen","freue","freust"],hint:"The verb must agree with 'er' and must go at the end of the dass-clause.",sSrc:"He says that he is happy about the event."},
{type:"mc",q:"Which sentence correctly uses a dass-clause?",opts:["Ich denke, dass organisiert Mia das Fest.","Ich denke, Mia dass das Fest organisiert.","Ich denke dass, Mia das Fest organisiert.","Ich denke, dass Mia das Fest organisiert."],ans:"Ich denke, dass Mia das Fest organisiert.",hint:"After this conjunction, the conjugated form must go last. Check each option for correct placement."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Wir wissen, {1} die Feier am Samstag {2}.",blanks:{"1":"dass","2":"stattfindet"},pool:["dass","stattfindet","findet","weil","statt"],hint:"The first blank needs the conjunction. The second needs the separable verb reunited at the end.",sSrc:"We know that the party takes place on Saturday."},
{type:"mc",q:"Mia says 'Ich hoffe, dass alle teilnehmen.' What does she hope?",opts:["That everyone organizes something","That everyone leaves early","That everyone participates","That everyone pays a fee"],ans:"That everyone participates",hint:"'Teilnehmen' means to take part in something."},
{type:"fb",s:"Hast du {1} auf den Wettbewerb?",a:["Lust"],opts:["Lust","Spaß","Fest","Interesse"],hint:"Which feminine noun means 'desire/mood' and pairs with 'haben auf'?",sSrc:"Do you feel like it for the competition?"},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Ich {1} mich, dass du am Wettbewerb {2}.",blanks:{"1":"freue","2":"teilnimmst"},pool:["freue","teilnimmst","nimmst","freuen","teil"],hint:"The main clause needs the reflexive verb for 'ich.' The dass-clause needs the verb for 'du' at the end.",sSrc:"I am happy that you are participating in the competition."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"sich freuen", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to be happy"},{trg:"sich treffen", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to meet up"},{trg:"teilnehmen", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to participate"},{trg:"stattfinden", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to take place"},{trg:"organisieren", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to organize"},{trg:"die Veranstaltung", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"the event"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"What does 'teilnehmen' mean?",opts:["to take place (similar)","to participate","to organize","to celebrate"],ans:"to participate",hint:"The prefix 'Teil' means part. You are taking part in something."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wann {1} das Sommerfest statt?",a:["findet"],opts:["findet","nimmt","macht","gibt"],hint:"A separable verb meaning 'to take place.' Match the subject 'das Sommerfest.'",sSrc:"When does the summer festival take place?"},
{type:"mc",q:"'Mia organisiert die Feier.' What is Mia doing?",opts:["attending the party","hosting the party","canceling the party","organizing the party"],ans:"organizing the party",hint:"Organisieren means to plan and arrange an event."}]}
,

{id:"deu_r9l5",title:"Ob oder dass?",icon:"📐",xp:20,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Ob oder dass?",desc:"Two powerful conjunctions unlock indirect speech: dass (that) introduces facts, ob (whether) introduces yes/no questions. Plus reflexive pronouns get their own dative forms, and you meet the ADUSO gang: five conjunctions that keep word order normal.",goals:["Reflexive pronouns: accusative vs dative","ob: indirect yes/no questions with verb-final","Coordinating conjunctions: und/oder/aber/denn/sondern (ADUSO)"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"sich verabreden", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to make a date / to arrange to meet",note:"Reflexive + separable. Ich verabrede mich mit Freunden.",example:"A: Verabredest du dich heute Abend?\nB: Ja, ich verabrede mich mit Lukas.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you meeting up tonight?\nB: Yes, I'm meeting up with Lukas.",funFact:"From 'Abrede' (agreement). Germans don't 'make plans,' they 'agree themselves.' The reflexive pronoun is essential: without 'sich,' it sounds like a legal contract."},
{type:"teach",trg:"sich unterhalten", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to chat / to converse",note:"Reflexive. Irregular: du unterhältst dich, er unterhält sich.",example:"A: Worüber unterhaltet ihr euch?\nB: Wir unterhalten uns über den Film.",exampleSrc:"A: What are you chatting about?\nB: We're chatting about the film.",funFact:"Literally 'to hold oneself under.' Also means 'to entertain.' 'Die Unterhaltung' = conversation OR entertainment. German efficiency: one word, two meanings."},
{type:"teach",trg:"diskutieren", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to discuss",note:"Regular, not reflexive. Diskutieren über + accusative.",example:"A: Wir diskutieren über das Spiel.\nB: Wer hat gewonnen?",exampleSrc:"A: We're discussing the game.\nB: Who won?",funFact:"Borrowed from Latin 'discutere' (to shake apart). Germans kept the Latin structure but gave it German endings. Easy cognate from English 'discuss.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"zuh\u00f6ren",src:"to listen (attentively)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb: zu + h\u00f6ren. Ich h\u00f6re zu. Dative person: jemandem zuh\u00f6ren.",example:"A: H\u00f6rst du mir zu?\nB: Ja, ich h\u00f6re dir zu.\nA: Gut, denn das ist wichtig.\nB: Ich h\u00f6re immer zu.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you listening to me?\nB: Yes, I am listening to you.\nA: Good, because this is important.\nB: I always listen.",funFact:"'Zuh\u00f6ren' = to listen attentively to a person. 'H\u00f6ren' = to hear something. The prefix 'zu' adds focus and direction. Germans appreciate the distinction and use 'Kannst du mir zuh\u00f6ren?' to ask for genuine attention, not just hearing."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wir haben uns für Samstag {1}.",a:["verabredet"],opts:["verabredet","unterhalten","diskutiert","zugehört"],hint:"Which past participle means made plans to meet?",sSrc:"We made plans for Saturday."},
{type:"mc",q:"Die Freunde sitzen im Cafe und unterhalten sich. Was machen sie?",opts:["They are eating","They are having a conversation","They are sleeping","They are arguing"],ans:"They are having a conversation",hint:"This reflexive verb describes friendly social talking."},
{type:"teach",trg:"vergessen", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to forget",note:"Irregular: du vergisst, er vergisst. Stem change e to i.",example:"A: Vergiss den Schlüssel nicht!\nB: Ich vergesse ihn nie!",exampleSrc:"A: Don't forget the key!\nB: I never forget it!",funFact:"The 'ver-' prefix often means 'wrongly' or 'away': verlaufen (get lost), versprechen (misspeak/promise). Vergessen = to 'get' something wrong in your memory."},
{type:"teach",trg:"verlieren", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to lose",note:"Irregular past, but regular present: ich verliere, du verlierst.",example:"A: Ich verliere immer meinen Schlüssel.\nB: Kauf dir eine Schlüsselbox!",exampleSrc:"A: I always lose my key.\nB: Buy yourself a key box!",funFact:"'Ver-' again! 'Verlieren' literally suggests something going astray. The opposite 'gewinnen' (to win) has no 'ver-' because winning is the normal state. Very German."},
{type:"teach",trg:"sich verlieben", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to fall in love",note:"Reflexive: ich verliebe mich in + accusative.",example:"A: Hast du dich schon mal verliebt?\nB: Ja, in meinen Hund!",exampleSrc:"A: Have you ever fallen in love?\nB: Yes, with my dog!",funFact:"Liebe = love. Sich verlieben = to love-ify yourself. The 'ver-' here means 'into a state.' You don't just love, you enter the STATE of loving. Very philosophical."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich habe meinen Schlüssel {1}. Wo ist er?",a:["verloren"],opts:["verloren","vergessen","geträumt","verabredet"],hint:"Which past participle means lost, as in misplaced?",sSrc:"I lost my key. Where is it?"},
{type:"teach",trg:"träumen", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to dream",note:"Regular: ich träume, du träumst. Träumen von + dative.",example:"A: Wovon träumst du?\nB: Ich träume von einer Reise nach Japan.",exampleSrc:"A: What do you dream about?\nB: I dream about a trip to Japan.",funFact:"'Der Traum' (the dream) shares a root with English 'dream.' In German you dream OF something (von), not ABOUT something. Preposition difference!"},
{type:"teach",trg:"sich ärgern", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to get annoyed / to be upset",note:"Reflexive: ich ärgere mich über + accusative (about).",example:"A: Warum ärgerst du dich?\nB: Ich ärgere mich über den Regen.",exampleSrc:"A: Why are you annoyed?\nB: I'm annoyed about the rain.",funFact:"'Ärger' = annoyance/trouble. Without 'sich,' ärgern means to annoy SOMEONE ELSE: 'Du ärgerst mich!' = You're annoying me! The reflexive flips the direction."},
{type:"tip",title:"Reflexive Pronouns: Accusative vs Dative",text:"Most reflexive verbs use ACCUSATIVE reflexive pronouns:\nich: mich, du: dich, er/sie/es: sich\nwir: uns, ihr: euch, sie/Sie: sich\n\nBut when there is ALSO a direct object, the reflexive switches to DATIVE:\nich: mir, du: dir, er/sie/es: sich\nwir: uns, ihr: euch, sie/Sie: sich\n\nCompare:\nIch wasche mich. (I wash myself. No other object.)\nIch wasche mir die Hände. (I wash my hands. Hände = acc object, so mir = dat.)\n\nOnly ich and du change: mich/mir, dich/dir. All others stay the same.",deepDive:{title:"When Does the Switch Happen?",text:"The rule is simple: a sentence can only have ONE accusative object. If the verb already has a direct object (die Hände, die Haare, die Zähne), the reflexive pronoun must step down to dative. This mostly matters with body parts and clothing:\nIch putze mir die Zähne. (I brush my teeth.)\nIch ziehe mir die Jacke an. (I put on my jacket.)\nIch kämme mir die Haare. (I comb my hair.)"}},
{type:"tip",title:"Separable Reflexive Verbs",text:"Some reflexive verbs are ALSO separable. The prefix splits off and goes to the end:\n\nsich anziehen: Ich ziehe mich an. (prefix 'an' at end)\nsich ausziehen: Ich ziehe mich aus. (prefix 'aus' at end)\nsich umziehen: Ich ziehe mich um. (prefix 'um' at end)\n\nThe reflexive pronoun stays right after the main verb.",deepDive:{title:"Separable reflexive verbs in Perfekt",text:"In Perfekt, separable reflexive verbs combine the ge- prefix:\nsich anziehen: Ich habe mich angezogen.\nsich ausziehen: Ich habe mich ausgezogen.\nge- goes between prefix and stem: an+ge+zogen = angezogen."}},
{type:"verb_table",title:"Dative Pronouns: Full Paradigm",label:"Personal pronouns across three cases",groups:[{label:"Singular",rows:[{pronoun:"1st sing.",form:"ich / mich / mir",src:"I / me (acc) / me (dat)"},{pronoun:"2nd sing. (informal)",form:"du / dich / dir",src:"you / you (acc) / you (dat)"},{pronoun:"3rd masc.",form:"er / ihn / ihm",src:"he / him (acc) / him (dat)"},{pronoun:"3rd fem.",form:"sie / sie / ihr",src:"she / her (acc) / her (dat)"},{pronoun:"3rd neut.",form:"es / es / ihm",src:"it / it (acc) / it (dat)"}]},{label:"Plural",rows:[{pronoun:"1st pl.",form:"wir / uns / uns",src:"we / us (acc) / us (dat)"},{pronoun:"2nd pl. (informal)",form:"ihr / euch / euch",src:"you all / you (acc) / you (dat)"},{pronoun:"3rd pl. / formal",form:"sie/Sie / sie/Sie / ihnen/Ihnen",src:"they/you / them/you (acc) / them/you (dat)"}]}],note:"Formal Sie (dative) = Ihnen (capital I).\nuns and euch are the same for accusative and dative.\nOnly ich and du change between acc and dat: mich/mir, dich/dir.",deepDive:{title:"A shortcut: uns and euch do double duty",text:"Uns is both accusative and dative for wir (we).\nEuch is both accusative and dative for ihr (you all).\n\nEr sieht uns. (He sees us, accusative)\nEr hilft uns. (He helps us, dative)\n\nSame form, context makes the case clear."}},
{type:"mc",q:"'Ich wasche ___ die Hände.' Which reflexive pronoun fits?",opts:["mich","sich","dir","mir"],ans:"mir",hint:"The hands are the accusative object. The reflexive must be dative."},
{type:"mc",q:"Which reflexive verb means 'to fall in love'?",opts:["sich unterhalten","sich verabreden","sich verlieben","sich ärgern"],ans:"sich verlieben",hint:"The 'ver-' prefix signals entering a new state. Love is the state here."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ärgerst du {1} über das Wetter?",a:["dich"],opts:["dich","dir","mich","sich"],hint:"No other object here. The reflexive is accusative for du.",sSrc:"Are you annoyed about the weather?"}
]},

// ─── Lesson: Ob, dass und ADUSO ───
{id:"deu_r9l6",title:"Ob, dass und ADUSO",icon:"📐",xp:20,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Ob, dass und ADUSO",desc:"Two subordinating conjunctions (ob and dass) that push verbs to the end, plus five coordinating conjunctions (ADUSO) that keep word order normal. Master the building blocks of complex German sentences.",goals:["Use ob for indirect yes/no questions","Compare ob (uncertainty) with dass (certainty)","Learn the five ADUSO conjunctions"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"ob", pos:"conj", gender:null,src:"whether / if",note:"Subordinating conjunction. Sends the verb to the END.\nob + subject + ... + verb (last).",example:"A: Weißt du, ob er morgen kommt?\nB: Nein, ich bin mir nicht sicher.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you know whether he's coming tomorrow?\nB: No, I'm not sure.",funFact:"'Ob' turns a yes/no question into an indirect one. 'Kommt er?' becomes 'Ich frage mich, ob er kommt.' Same question, but embedded. The verb jumps to the end, just like with dass and weil."},
{type:"teach",trg:"wahr",src:"true",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. 'Das stimmt' = that is correct (informal). 'Das ist wahr' = that is true (factual).",example:"A: Stimmt es, dass er aus Italien kommt?\nB: Ja, das ist wahr.\nA: Und er spricht kein Deutsch?\nB: Das war fr\u00fcher wahr, aber jetzt spricht er gut.",exampleSrc:"A: Is it true that he comes from Italy?\nB: Yes, that is true.\nA: And he speaks no German?\nB: That was true before, but now he speaks well.",funFact:"'Wahr' gives German 'wahrhaftig' (truly), 'w\u00e4hrend' (during, literally 'while true'), and 'Wahrheit' (truth). When a German says 'Das ist doch wahr!', the 'doch' adds a tone of self-evident certainty."},
{type:"tip",title:"ob: Indirect Yes/No Questions",text:"'Ob' means 'whether' and turns a yes/no question into an indirect one.\nThe verb goes to the END after ob.\n\nDirect: Kommt er morgen?\nIndirect: Ich weiß nicht, ob er morgen kommt.\n\nCommon triggers for ob:\nfragen (to ask), wissen (to know), sicher sein (to be sure)\n\nCompare with dass (that), which states FACTS:\nIch weiß, dass er morgen kommt. (I know THAT he comes.)\nIch weiß nicht, ob er morgen kommt. (I don't know WHETHER he comes.)\n\ndass = certainty. ob = uncertainty.",deepDive:{title:"Dass vs Ob: The Quick Test",text:"Ask yourself: 'Can I answer this with yes or no?'\nIf YES: use ob.\nIch frage, ob du kommst. (Will you come? Yes/no.)\nIf NO: use dass.\nIch weiß, dass du kommst. (You're coming. Fact.)\n\nBoth send the verb to the end. The difference is certainty vs uncertainty."}},
{type:"mc",q:"'Ich frage mich, ___ er heute kommt.' Which conjunction fits?",opts:["dass","weil","ob","denn"],ans:"ob",hint:"He might come, he might not. You are uncertain."},
{type:"fb",s:"Weißt du, {1} das Kino heute offen ist?",a:["ob"],opts:["ob","dass","weil","und"],hint:"You genuinely don't know. Yes or no question hidden inside.",sSrc:"Do you know whether the cinema is open today?"},
{type:"tip",title:"Coordinating Conjunctions: ADUSO",text:"Five conjunctions that keep NORMAL word order (verb stays in position 2):\n\nA: aber (but)\nD: denn (because, in main clauses)\nU: und (and)\nS: sondern (but rather, after a negative)\nO: oder (or)\n\nThese connect two main clauses. The verb does NOT move.\nIch spiele Tennis, und er spielt Fußball.\nSie kommt nicht, sondern sie bleibt zu Hause.\n\nContrast with dass/ob/weil: those are SUBORDINATING and push the verb to the end.",deepDive:{title:"Aber vs Sondern",text:"Both mean 'but,' with different uses:\n\nAber = general contrast:\nIch bin müde, aber ich gehe ins Kino.\n\nSondern = correction after a negative:\nIch trinke nicht Kaffee, sondern Tee.\n(Not coffee, but RATHER tea.)\n\nSondern always follows 'nicht' or 'kein.' If there is no negation, use aber."}},
{type:"mc",q:"'Er kommt nicht aus Berlin, ___ aus Hamburg.' Which word corrects the false statement?",opts:["aber","denn","oder","sondern"],ans:"sondern",hint:"After 'nicht,' this conjunction replaces a wrong idea with the correct one."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich möchte mitkommen, {1} ich habe keine Zeit.",a:["aber"],opts:["aber","sondern","denn","ob"],hint:"A general contrast. No negation before this conjunction.",sSrc:"I would like to come along, but I have no time."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Ich weiß, dass er sich verliebt hat.' What does 'dass' introduce here?",opts:["A yes/no question","A reason","A time clause","A fact he knows"],ans:"A fact he knows",hint:"There is certainty here. Dass introduces certainties, ob introduces doubt."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Ich frage mich, {1} sie {2} heute {3}.",blanks:{"1":"ob","2":"sich","3":"verabredet"},pool:["ob","sich","verabredet","dass","mich","verliebt"],hint:"Uncertain question: WHETHER she arranges to meet today. Verb to end.",sSrc:"I wonder whether she is meeting up today."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Ich putze mir die Zähne.' Why is it 'mir' and not 'mich'?",opts:["Putzen always needs dative","Zähne takes the accusative","Mir sounds more polite here","There is no real reason"],ans:"Zähne takes the accusative",hint:"A sentence can only have one direct object. The body part fills that role."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wir unterhalten {1} über den neuen Film.",a:["uns"],opts:["uns","euch","sich","mich"],hint:"Wir = we. The reflexive pronoun for wir is the same in acc and dat.",sSrc:"We are chatting about the new film."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Er fragt sie, {1} er weiß nicht, {2} sie ihn {3}.",blanks:{"1":"denn","2":"ob","3":"liebt"},pool:["denn","ob","liebt","dass","verliebt","aber"],hint:"Two different conjunctions needed: one coordinating (keeps V2 order) and one for an indirect yes/no question.",sSrc:"He asks her because he does not know whether she loves him."},
{type:"mc",q:"Which conjunction keeps normal V2 word order?",opts:["und","dass","ob","weil"],ans:"und",hint:"ADUSO conjunctions: aber, denn, sondern, oder (plus one more). All keep V2."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich vergesse nie, {1} du mir geholfen hast.",a:["dass"],opts:["dass","ob","denn","und"],hint:"You know for certain she helped. This is a stated fact.",sSrc:"I never forget that you helped me."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Sie {1} sich, {2} sie morgen frei {3}.",blanks:{"1":"fragt","2":"ob","3":"hat"},pool:["fragt","ob","hat","weiß","dass","ist"],hint:"She asks herself WHETHER she has tomorrow off. Verb to end after ob.",sSrc:"She asks herself whether she has tomorrow off."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Ich ärgere mich, denn er vergisst alles.' What does 'denn' mean here?",opts:["but (contrast)","whether (doubt)","because (reason)","that (fact)"],ans:"because (reason)",hint:"Denn explains the cause while keeping main clause word order."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"sich verabreden", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to arrange to meet"},{trg:"sich unterhalten", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to chat"},{trg:"vergessen", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to forget"},{trg:"sich verlieben", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to fall in love"},{trg:"ob", pos:"conj", gender:null,src:"whether"},{trg:"sondern",src:"but rather"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"anders",src:"different / differently",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"Indeclinable adverb/adjective. 'Das ist anders' = that is different. 'Anders als' = different from.",example:"A: Das ist hier wirklich anders als in Italien.\nB: Ja, was ist anders f\u00fcr dich?\nA: Die Regeln! Alles hat Regeln.\nB: Das stimmt. Deutschland ist anders.",exampleSrc:"A: This is really different here from Italy.\nB: Yes, what is different for you?\nA: The rules! Everything has rules.\nB: That's true. Germany is different.",funFact:"'Anders' is one of the most useful words in German. It never takes endings: always 'anders,' never 'anderse' or 'anderer' in this adverb use. Perfect for expressing surprise, comparison, or cultural observations."}]}
,

{id:"deu_r9l7",title:"Digital und analog",icon:"📱",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Digital und analog",desc:"Verumius discovers German media culture: from blogs and podcasts to paper magazines and comic books. The old and the new, side by side.",goals:["Learn 14 words for media and digital life","Review reflexive verbs with sich","Practice dass and ob subordinate clauses"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Blog", pos:"noun", gender:"m",src:"the blog",note:"Masculine noun. Plural: die Blogs. Borrowed from English.",example:"A: Liest du einen Blog über Kochen?\nB: Ja, ich lese jeden Tag einen neuen Blog.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you read a blog about cooking?\nB: Yes, I read a new blog every day.",funFact:"Germans adopted 'Blog' directly from English but gave it a masculine article. Some Germans say 'das Blog' (neuter), which causes fierce grammar debates online."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das E-Book", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"the e-book",note:"Neuter noun. Plural: die E-Books. Pronounced like English.",example:"A: Liest du lieber E-Books oder Bücher?\nB: Ich lese lieber E-Books, weil sie leichter sind.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you prefer reading e-books or books?\nB: I prefer e-books because they are lighter.",funFact:"Germany has a fixed book price law (Buchpreisbildung). Every bookstore must sell the same book at the same price. E-Books are included since 2016."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Comic", pos:"noun", gender:"m",src:"the comic",note:"Masculine noun. Plural: die Comics.",example:"A: Hast du als Kind Comics gelesen?\nB: Ja, ich habe viele Comics gesammelt.",exampleSrc:"A: Did you read comics as a child?\nB: Yes, I collected many comics.",funFact:"Germany's most famous comic is 'Werner,' about a plumber and his motorcycle. Asterix is also hugely popular in German translation, with brilliant wordplay."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Sendung", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"the TV show / broadcast",note:"Feminine noun. Plural: die Sendungen. From 'senden' (to send/broadcast).",example:"A: Welche Sendung schaust du heute Abend?\nB: Ich schaue eine Sendung über Natur.",exampleSrc:"A: Which show are you watching tonight?\nB: I'm watching a show about nature.",funFact:"'Sendung mit der Maus' is Germany's most beloved children's show, running since 1971. The orange mouse explains how things work. Even adults watch it."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was liest man auf einem Bildschirm, aber nicht in einem Laden?",opts:["Das E-Book","Die Zeitschrift","Den Comic","Das Programm"],ans:"Das E-Book",hint:"This digital format replaced printed texts for many readers."},
{type:"fb",s:"Mein Lieblings-{1} schreibt über Reisen und Essen.",a:["Blog"],opts:["Blog","Comic","Sendung","Programm"],hint:"Which English loanword describes an online journal?",sSrc:"My favorite blog writes about travel and food."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Zeitschrift", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"the magazine",note:"Feminine noun. Plural: die Zeitschriften. Compound: Zeit (time) + Schrift (writing).",example:"A: Kaufst du noch Zeitschriften?\nB: Nein, ich lese alles online.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you still buy magazines?\nB: No, I read everything online.",funFact:"Zeit + Schrift = time-writing. A magazine captures a moment in time. Der Spiegel and Stern are Germany's most famous magazines, read in every doctor's waiting room."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Programm", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"the program / schedule",note:"Neuter noun. Plural: die Programme. Also means TV schedule.",example:"A: Was kommt heute im Programm?\nB: Um acht kommt eine neue Sendung.",exampleSrc:"A: What is on the schedule today?\nB: At eight there is a new show.",funFact:"Germans still say 'Was kommt im Programm?' when asking what is on TV. The word covers software, TV listings, theater schedules, and political platforms."},
{type:"teach",trg:"manch",src:"some / many a",pos:"pron",gender:null,note:"Determiner/pronoun. 'Mancher' (m), 'manche' (f/pl), 'manches' (n). Often used in plural: manche Leute = some people.",example:"A: Lesen manche Leute noch Zeitungen?\nB: Ja, manche Leute lesen jeden Tag eine Zeitung.\nA: Und manche surfen nur im Internet?\nB: Genau, manche machen beides.",exampleSrc:"A: Do some people still read newspapers?\nB: Yes, some people read a newspaper every day.\nA: And some only surf the internet?\nB: Exactly, some do both.",funFact:"'Manch' belongs to the family of der-words (mancher, dieser, jener). It feels slightly literary compared to 'einige' (a few) or 'einige Leute.' Germans use it when painting a picture: 'Mancher Leser...' has a more narrative tone than 'Einige Leser...'"},
{type:"mc",q:"Verumius fragt: 'Was kommt heute im Programm?' What is he asking about?",opts:["What software to install","What is on TV tonight","What is for dinner","When the train leaves"],ans:"What is on TV tonight",hint:"'Programm' here refers to the broadcast schedule."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich lese eine {1} über Reisen.",a:["Zeitschrift"],opts:["Zeitschrift","Sendung","Blog","Programm"],hint:"Which feminine noun means a printed magazine you can hold?",sSrc:"I read a magazine about travel."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Radio", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"the radio",note:"Neuter noun. Plural: die Radios.",example:"A: Hörst du Radio im Auto?\nB: Ja, ich höre immer Radio beim Fahren.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you listen to the radio in the car?\nB: Yes, I always listen to the radio while driving.",funFact:"German public radio is funded by the Rundfunkbeitrag, a monthly fee every household pays (about 18 euros). Germans debate this fee as passionately as the weather."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Tipp", pos:"noun", gender:"m",src:"the tip / piece of advice",note:"Masculine noun. Plural: die Tipps. Borrowed from English.",example:"A: Hast du einen Tipp für mich?\nB: Ja, informiere dich vorher im Internet.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a tip for me?\nB: Yes, inform yourself beforehand on the internet.",funFact:"Germans spell it with double 'p' unlike English 'tip.' The word entered German in the 19th century from English horse racing jargon."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Heft", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"the notebook / issue (of a magazine)",note:"Neuter noun. Plural: die Hefte. Two meanings depending on context.",example:"A: Hast du das neue Heft gekauft?\nB: Nein, ich kaufe keine Hefte mehr.",exampleSrc:"A: Did you buy the new issue?\nB: No, I don't buy issues anymore.",funFact:"Every German schoolchild has a Heft for each subject: Matheheft, Deutschheft, Englischheft. The word originally meant a handle (what you 'hold'), then shifted to a bound booklet."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Das Heft' can mean two things. Which pair is correct?",opts:["Book and a letter","Blog and an email","Notebook and issue","Radio and a show"],ans:"Notebook and issue",hint:"Think about what you write in at school and what you buy at a newsstand."},
{type:"fb",s:"Heute Abend kommt eine interessante {1} im Fernsehen.",a:["Sendung"],opts:["Sendung","Blog","Comic","Heft"],hint:"A television show or broadcast. Feminine noun from 'senden' (to send).",sSrc:"Tonight there is an interesting show on television."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"der Blog", pos:"noun", gender:"m",src:"the blog"},{trg:"die Zeitschrift", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"the magazine"},{trg:"das Radio", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"the radio"},{trg:"der Tipp", pos:"noun", gender:"m",src:"the tip"}]}
]},

// ─── Lesson: Digitale Hobbys ───
{id:"deu_r9l8",title:"Digitale Hobbys",icon:"📷",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Digitale Hobbys",desc:"Photographing, chatting, surfing, collecting: the digital and analog hobbies of modern German life. Plus cameras, books, and how to borrow things.",goals:["Learn verbs for digital and analog hobbies","Practice dass and ob in context","Expand vocabulary for media and technology"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"fotografieren", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to photograph",note:"Regular: ich fotografiere, du fotografierst. Past: fotografiert (no ge- prefix).",example:"A: Fotografierst du gern?\nB: Ja, ich fotografiere am liebsten Tiere.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you like photographing?\nB: Yes, I like photographing animals the most.",funFact:"Like all -ieren verbs (studieren, telefonieren, informieren), fotografieren skips the ge- prefix in past tense: 'Ich habe fotografiert,' never 'gefotografiert.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"chatten", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to chat (online)",note:"Regular: ich chatte, du chattest. Past: gechattet.",example:"A: Mit wem chattest du?\nB: Ich chatte mit meiner Schwester.",exampleSrc:"A: Who are you chatting with?\nB: I'm chatting with my sister.",funFact:"Unlike -ieren verbs, 'chatten' DOES get the ge- prefix: gechattet. Why? Because it was borrowed recently and conjugated like a regular German verb, not through French/Latin."},
{type:"teach",trg:"surfen", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to surf (the internet)",note:"Regular: ich surfe, du surfst. 'Im Internet surfen' = to browse the web.",example:"A: Was machst du gerade?\nB: Ich surfe im Internet.",exampleSrc:"A: What are you doing right now?\nB: I'm surfing the internet.",funFact:"Germans say 'im Internet surfen' like riding waves of information. The verb keeps its English pronunciation but gets German endings: surfe, surfst, surft."},
{type:"teach",trg:"sammeln", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to collect",note:"Regular: ich sammle, du sammelst. Past: gesammelt.",example:"A: Was sammelst du?\nB: Ich sammle alte Comics und Briefmarken.",exampleSrc:"A: What do you collect?\nB: I collect old comics and stamps.",funFact:"Germans are serious collectors. Briefmarkensammler (stamp collectors), Münzsammler (coin collectors), and Bierdeckelsammler (beer coaster collectors) all have dedicated clubs and meetups."},
{type:"teach",trg:"informieren", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to inform",note:"Regular: ich informiere. Reflexive: sich informieren = to find out, to inform oneself.",example:"A: Wo informierst du dich über Nachrichten?\nB: Ich informiere mich online.",exampleSrc:"A: Where do you get your news?\nB: I inform myself online.",funFact:"'Sich informieren' is reflexive: you inform YOURSELF. Germans love reflexive verbs for actions you do for your own benefit: sich erinnern, sich freuen, sich informieren."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Ich informiere mich im Internet.' Why is 'mich' in this sentence?",opts:["Because informieren is used reflexively here","Because the internet requires accusative","Because ich always needs mich","Because the sentence is a question form"],ans:"Because informieren is used reflexively here",hint:"The action of informing loops back to the subject. Think: I inform MYSELF."},
{type:"fb",s:"Er {1} sich über das Programm.",a:["informiert"],opts:["informiert","informieren","informiere","informierst"],hint:"Third person singular: er + verb. Which ending fits?",sSrc:"He informs himself about the program."},
{type:"mc",q:"Mia sagt, dass sie jeden Tag einen Blog ___.",opts:["lesen","liest","lese","lest"],ans:"liest",hint:"In a dass-clause the verb goes to the end. Mia is 'sie,' so the verb needs the third person form."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich weiß nicht, ob er gern {1}.",a:["chattet"],opts:["chattet","chatten","chatte","chattest"],hint:"After 'ob' the verb moves to the end. The subject is 'er.'",sSrc:"I don't know if he likes to chat."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Sie fragt, ob Verumius {1} gern {2} und ob er Zeitschriften {3}.",blanks:{"1":"sich","2":"informiert","3":"sammelt"},pool:["sich","informiert","sammelt","mich","surft","chatten"],hint:"Both clauses are indirect questions introduced by 'ob.' First blank: the verb 'informieren' is always used reflexively. Second blank: conjugate for 'er' and move to the end.",sSrc:"She asks whether Verumius likes to inform himself and whether he collects magazines."},
{type:"mc",q:"How do you form the Partizip II of verbs ending in -ieren?",opts:["Normal ge- prefix: ge + stem + t","No ge- prefix: just stem + t","Double ge-: gege + stem + t","No change at all"],ans:"No ge- prefix: just stem + t",hint:"Think about studieren, telefonieren, informieren. They all follow the same pattern."},
{type:"fb",s:"Er sagt, dass er alte Comics {1}.",a:["sammelt"],opts:["sammelt","sammeln","sammle","gesammelt"],hint:"In a dass-clause the conjugated verb goes to the end. Subject is 'er.'",sSrc:"He says that he collects old comics."},
{type:"mc",q:"Verumius surft im Internet. Er findet einen Blog. Was macht er?",opts:["He browses online and finds a blog","He goes surfing at the beach (alternative)","He collects magazines","He listens to the radio"],ans:"He browses online and finds a blog",hint:"'Im Internet surfen' means browsing, not ocean waves."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Lukas erzählt, dass er {1} für Sendungen über Natur {2} und dass er Tipps im {3} gehört hat.",blanks:{"1":"sich","2":"interessiert","3":"Radio"},pool:["sich","interessiert","Radio","mich","informiert","Blog"],hint:"The first dass-clause contains a reflexive verb about having interest in something. The reflexive pronoun for 'er' goes before the verb. He heard tips on which broadcast device?",sSrc:"Lukas tells us that he is interested in shows about nature and that he heard tips on the radio."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"der Blog", pos:"noun", gender:"m",src:"the blog"},{trg:"die Sendung", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"the TV show"},{trg:"das Radio", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"the radio"},{trg:"fotografieren", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to photograph"},{trg:"chatten", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to chat online"},{trg:"sammeln", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to collect"},{trg:"die Zeitschrift", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"the magazine"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Fotoapparat", pos:"noun", gender:"m",src:"the camera (old style)",note:"Masculine compound: Foto + Apparat. Plural: die Fotoapparate.",example:"A: Hast du deinen Fotoapparat dabei?\nB: Nein, ich fotografiere nur mit dem Handy.\nA: Mein Opa hat noch einen alten Fotoapparat.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have your camera with you?\nB: No, I only take photos with my phone.\nA: My grandpa still has an old camera.",funFact:"Before digital cameras, every German family had a Fotoapparat for vacations. Leica, a German brand, invented the 35mm camera in 1925."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Kamera", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"the camera",note:"Feminine. Plural: die Kameras. Modern, general word for camera.",example:"A: Welche Kamera benutzt du?\nB: Eine kleine Digitalkamera.\nA: Die Fotos sind wirklich gut!",exampleSrc:"A: Which camera do you use?\nB: A small digital camera.\nA: The photos are really good!",funFact:"Germany's camera industry shaped photography worldwide. Zeiss lenses, Leica cameras, and Rollei twin-lens reflexes were all born in Germany."},
{type:"teach",trg:"online", pos:"adv", gender:null,src:"online",note:"Adverb and adjective. Pronounced like English. Online sein = to be online.",example:"A: Bist du gerade online?\nB: Ja, ich surfe im Internet.\nA: Schick mir den Link!",exampleSrc:"A: Are you online right now?\nB: Yes, I'm surfing the internet.\nA: Send me the link!",funFact:"Germans adopted 'online' wholesale from English. The phrase 'online gehen' (to go online) is used by all generations."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Buch", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"the book",note:"Neuter. Plural: die Bücher (with Umlaut!).",example:"A: Was liest du gerade?\nB: Ein Buch über deutsche Geschichte.\nA: Klingt interessant! Leihst du es mir?",exampleSrc:"A: What are you reading?\nB: A book about German history.\nA: Sounds interesting! Will you lend it to me?",funFact:"Germany publishes about 70,000 new books per year, making it the third largest book market in the world after the US and China."},
{type:"teach",trg:"ausleihen", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to borrow / to lend out",note:"Separable: ich leihe aus. Perfekt: hat ausgeliehen. In der Bibliothek Bücher ausleihen.",example:"A: Kann ich das Buch ausleihen?\nB: Ja, du kannst es zwei Wochen behalten.\nA: Danke! Ich bringe es pünktlich zurück.",exampleSrc:"A: Can I borrow the book?\nB: Yes, you can keep it for two weeks.\nA: Thanks! I'll bring it back on time.",funFact:"German libraries are very popular. Over 200 million items are borrowed per year. Many now also lend e-books, video games, and even kitchen appliances."},

{"type":"mc","q":"Was ist 'der Fotoapparat'?","opts":["the camera (old style)","the telephone","the television","the radio"],"ans":"the camera (old style)","hint":"An older device used to take photographs."},
{"type":"mc","q":"Was ist 'die Kamera'?","opts":["the camera","the lamp","the clock","the screen"],"ans":"the camera","hint":"A modern device for taking photos or video."},
{"type":"fb","s":"Ich lese gern ein gutes {1}.","a":["Buch"],"opts":["Buch","Film","Lied","Spiel"],"hint":"Pages bound together with a story inside.","sSrc":"I like reading a good book."},
{"type":"mc","q":"Was bedeutet 'ausleihen'?","opts":["to borrow","to buy","to sell","to return"],"ans":"to borrow","hint":"Taking something temporarily with a plan to give it back."}]}
,

// U9 L6: Nach dem Lauf - Story climax (post-run park scene)
{id:"deu_r9l9",title:"Nach dem Lauf",icon:"☕",xp:20,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Nach dem Lauf",desc:"The run is over. Verumius stretches in the park while Lukas arrives with coffees on his cargo bike. A text from Dr. Yilmaz reminds everyone why community matters.",goals:["Learn animal and leisure vocabulary","Review reflexive verbs, dass, ob, and conjunctions","Combine multiple grammar patterns in real conversation"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Katze", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"the cat",note:"Feminine. Plural: die Katzen.",example:"A: Hast du ein Haustier?\nB: Ja, ich habe eine Katze. Sie heißt Mimi.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a pet?\nB: Yes, I have a cat. Her name is Mimi.",funFact:"Germany has about 15 million pet cats, making them the most popular pet. The idiom 'die Katze im Sack kaufen' (to buy the cat in the bag) means to buy something sight unseen."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Vogel", pos:"noun", gender:"m",src:"the bird",note:"Masculine. Plural: die Vögel (with Umlaut!).",example:"A: Hörst du den Vogel?\nB: Ja, er singt wunderschön!",exampleSrc:"A: Do you hear the bird?\nB: Yes, it sings beautifully!",funFact:"'Einen Vogel haben' (to have a bird) means to be crazy in German. People tap their forehead to show someone 'hat einen Vogel.' Careful with this gesture!"},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Pferd", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"the horse",note:"Neuter. Plural: die Pferde.",example:"A: Warst du schon mal auf einem Pferd?\nB: Nein, aber ich möchte es versuchen.",exampleSrc:"A: Have you ever been on a horse?\nB: No, but I would like to try.",funFact:"German has a great expression: 'Das beste Pferd im Stall' (the best horse in the stable) means the top performer. Germany's equestrian tradition runs deep."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Tier", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"the animal",note:"Neuter. Plural: die Tiere. From Old High German 'tior.'",example:"A: Was ist dein Lieblingstier?\nB: Ich mag Hunde, aber auch Katzen.",exampleSrc:"A: What is your favorite animal?\nB: I like dogs, but also cats.",funFact:"The German word 'Tierarzt' (animal doctor) is wonderfully literal. 'Tierschutz' (animal protection) is taken very seriously in Germany, with animal welfare written into the constitution since 2002."},
{type:"mc",q:"Lukas fragt: 'Hast du ein Haustier?' Verumius sagt: 'Ja, eine Katze.' Was ist eine Katze?",opts:["a cat","a dog","a bird","a horse"],ans:"a cat",hint:"This feminine noun names a popular pet that purrs."},
{type:"fb",s:"Im Park singt ein {1} im Baum.",a:"Vogel",opts:["Vogel","Pferd","Katze","Tier"],hint:"Which masculine animal is known for singing from branches?",sSrc:"In the park a bird sings in the tree."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Park", pos:"noun", gender:"m",src:"the park",note:"Masculine. Plural: die Parks. Borrowed from English/French.",example:"A: Wo treffen wir uns?\nB: Im Park, neben der großen Eiche.",exampleSrc:"A: Where do we meet?\nB: In the park, next to the big oak.",funFact:"Berlin alone has over 2,500 public parks. The Tiergarten (animal garden) in Berlin was originally a royal hunting ground. Now it is the city's green lung."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Tour", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"the tour",note:"Feminine. Plural: die Touren. Also means 'a trip' or 'a route.'",example:"A: Machen wir am Samstag eine Radtour?\nB: Gute Idee! Ich freue mich darauf.",exampleSrc:"A: Shall we do a bike tour on Saturday?\nB: Good idea! I look forward to it.",funFact:"'Radtour' (bike tour), 'Wandertour' (hiking tour), 'Stadttour' (city tour). Germans love compound nouns, and they love organized outings even more."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Workshop", pos:"noun", gender:"m",src:"the workshop",note:"Masculine. Plural: die Workshops. Anglicism used in German.",example:"A: Ich besuche einen Workshop über Fotografie.\nB: Das klingt interessant!",exampleSrc:"A: I am attending a workshop on photography.\nB: That sounds interesting!",funFact:"Germans borrow many English words but pronounce them differently. 'Workshop' becomes 'VORK-shop' with a German W. The original German word is 'Werkstatt,' but Workshop sounds trendier."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Zirkus", pos:"noun", gender:"m",src:"the circus",note:"Masculine. Plural: die Zirkusse.",example:"A: Warst du schon im Zirkus?\nB: Ja, als Kind. Ich fand die Tiere toll.",exampleSrc:"A: Have you been to the circus?\nB: Yes, as a child. I loved the animals.",funFact:"The famous Circus Roncalli in Germany stopped using real animals in 2018 and replaced them with holograms. Technology meets tradition!"},
{type:"mc",q:"Lukas sagt: 'Treffen wir uns im Park?' Verumius antwortet: 'Gern! Machen wir eine Tour mit dem Rad?' Was ist eine Tour?",opts:["ein Haustier","ein Ausflug oder eine Route","ein Verein","ein Lied"],ans:"ein Ausflug oder eine Route",hint:"This feminine noun describes an organized outing or trip, often combined with Rad- or Wander-."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Zoo", pos:"noun", gender:"m",src:"the zoo",note:"Masculine. Short for 'der Zoologische Garten.'",example:"A: Gehen wir morgen in den Zoo?\nB: Ja, ich möchte die Elefanten sehen.",exampleSrc:"A: Shall we go to the zoo tomorrow?\nB: Yes, I want to see the elephants.",funFact:"The Berlin Zoo, opened in 1844, is the oldest zoo in Germany and one of the most species-rich in the world, with over 20,000 animals."},
{type:"fb",s:"Am Samstag besuche ich einen {1} über Fotografie.",a:["Workshop"],opts:["Workshop","Zirkus","Zoo","Park"],hint:"An English loanword for a hands-on learning event. Pronounced VORK-shop in German.",sSrc:"On Saturday I am attending a workshop on photography."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Krimi", pos:"noun", gender:"m",src:"the crime novel / thriller",note:"Masculine. Short for 'der Kriminalroman.' Plural: die Krimis.",example:"A: Was liest du gerade?\nB: Einen Krimi von Sebastian Fitzek. Sehr spannend!",exampleSrc:"A: What are you reading right now?\nB: A thriller by Sebastian Fitzek. Very exciting!",funFact:"Germans love their Krimis. The TV show 'Tatort' (crime scene) has been running since 1970 and is a Sunday night ritual. Bars even host Tatort viewing parties."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was liest Verumius gerade? Einen spannenden Krimi! Was ist ein Krimi?",opts:["ein Park","ein Zirkus","ein Kriminalroman","ein Zoo"],ans:"ein Kriminalroman",hint:"'Krimi' is a shortened form of a compound word. Think mystery, murders, detectives. What is the full word?"},
{type:"fb",s:"Gehen wir morgen in den {1}? Ich möchte die Elefanten sehen.",a:["Zoo"],opts:["Zoo","Park","Krimi","Workshop"],hint:"A short word for the place where you can see exotic animals. Berlin's is from 1844.",sSrc:"Shall we go to the zoo tomorrow? I want to see the elephants."},
{type:"mc",q:"Verumius fragt: 'Warst du schon im Zirkus?' Was kann man im Zirkus sehen?",opts:["Bücher und Krimis","Workshops über Fotografie","Vögel im Wald","Tiere und Artisten"],ans:"Tiere und Artisten",hint:"A place of entertainment with performers and animals. Circus Roncalli uses holograms instead of real animals."}]},

// ─── Lesson: Alles zusammen üben ───
{id:"deu_r9l10",title:"Alles zusammen üben",icon:"🧩",xp:20,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Alles zusammen üben",desc:"Put everything together: reflexive verbs, dass and ob clauses, coordinating conjunctions, and all the vocabulary from animals to thrillers. Prove you can build complex German sentences.",goals:["Combine reflexive verbs with subordinate clauses","Use ob, dass, weil, denn, und in context","Describe interests, plans, and opinions"]},
{type:"mc",q:"Verumius sagt, dass Dr. Yilmaz über Gemeinschaft schreibt. Welcher Nebensatz ist richtig?",opts:["Sie schreibt, dass ist Gemeinschaft wichtig.","Sie schreibt, dass wichtig Gemeinschaft ist.","Sie schreibt, ist dass Gemeinschaft wichtig.","Sie schreibt, dass Gemeinschaft wichtig ist."],ans:"Sie schreibt, dass Gemeinschaft wichtig ist.",hint:"In this type of subordinate structure, the conjugated form moves to the last position."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich frage mich, {1} der Zoo am Sonntag offen ist.",a:"ob",opts:["ob","dass","weil","denn"],hint:"Which conjunction introduces an indirect yes/no question?",sSrc:"I wonder whether the zoo is open on Sunday."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Lukas sagt, {1} er {2} auf die Tour {3}.",blanks:{1:"dass",2:"sich",3:"freut"},pool:["dass","sich","freut","ob","mich","lacht"],hint:"Lukas reports a certainty, not a doubt. The verb 'freuen' is reflexive: it needs a pronoun referring back to the subject 'er.' Verb goes last.",sSrc:"Lukas says that he is looking forward to the tour."},
{type:"mc",q:"Mia liest Krimis, ___ Lukas mag Sport. Fill in the missing connector.",opts:["aber","denn","oder","und"],ans:"und",hint:"Both facts are true and simply added together without contrast."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die Katze schläft, {1} sie müde ist.",a:"weil",opts:["weil","und","oder","denn"],hint:"This subordinating conjunction means 'because' and sends the verb to the end.",sSrc:"The cat is sleeping because it is tired."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Er fragt, {1} sie {2} für Pferde {3}.",blanks:{1:"ob",2:"sich",3:"interessiert"},pool:["ob","sich","interessiert","dass","mich","fragt"],hint:"Indirect yes/no question with a reflexive verb. Verb goes last.",sSrc:"He asks whether she is interested in horses."},
{type:"mc",q:"Welcher Satz kombiniert 'sich fühlen' und 'denn' korrekt?",opts:["Ich mich fühle gut, denn ich habe Sport gemacht.","Ich fühle mich gut, denn ich Sport gemacht habe.","Ich fühle mich gut, denn ich habe Sport gemacht.","Ich fühle gut mich, denn ich habe Sport gemacht."],ans:"Ich fühle mich gut, denn ich habe Sport gemacht.",hint:"This coordinating conjunction keeps normal word order in the second part."},
{type:"fb",s:"Sie ärgert {1} über den Lärm im Park.",a:"sich",opts:["sich","mich","dich","uns"],hint:"Third person reflexive pronoun for 'she' in a reflexive verb.",sSrc:"She is annoyed about the noise in the park."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Verumius weiß nicht, ob er morgen eine Radtour macht oder ob er in den Zoo geht.' How many ob clauses are in this sentence?",opts:["Two","One","Three","None"],ans:"Two",hint:"Count the word 'ob.' Each one opens a new indirect question."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Er {1} sich, {2} der Krimi spannend ist, {3} er ihn lesen will.",blanks:{1:"fragt",2:"ob",3:"denn"},pool:["fragt","ob","denn","dass","freut","weil"],hint:"He asks himself (reflexive), whether... because... Two different conjunctions needed.",sSrc:"He asks himself whether the thriller is exciting, because he wants to read it."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"die Katze", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"the cat"},{trg:"der Vogel", pos:"noun", gender:"m",src:"the bird"},{trg:"das Pferd", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"the horse"},{trg:"das Tier", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"the animal"},{trg:"der Park", pos:"noun", gender:"m",src:"the park"},{trg:"der Krimi", pos:"noun", gender:"m",src:"the thriller"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"'Er interessiert sich für Krimis.' What does this mean?",opts:["He wrote a thriller","He is interested in thrillers","He forgot the thriller (alternative)","He lost the thriller"],ans:"He is interested in thrillers",hint:"'Sich interessieren für' describes a feeling of curiosity or attraction toward a topic. What does that feeling translate to?"},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Gemeinschaft", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"the community",note:"Feminine. From gemein (common) + -schaft (collective suffix). Plural: die Gemeinschaften.",example:"A: Die Gemeinschaft im Verein ist toll.\nB: Ja, alle helfen sich gegenseitig.\nA: Das ist das Beste am Vereinsleben.",exampleSrc:"A: The community in the club is great.\nB: Yes, everyone helps each other.\nA: That's the best thing about club life.",funFact:"Gemeinschaft vs. Gesellschaft is a famous sociological contrast coined by Ferdinand Tonnies in 1887. Gemeinschaft is warm personal bonds, Gesellschaft is formal society."},
{type:"teach",trg:"interessieren (sich)", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to be interested (in)",note:"Reflexive: sich interessieren für + accusative. Ich interessiere mich für Musik.",example:"A: Wofür interessierst du dich?\nB: Ich interessiere mich für Fotografie.\nA: Dann musst du die Ausstellung sehen!",exampleSrc:"A: What are you interested in?\nB: I'm interested in photography.\nA: Then you have to see the exhibition!",funFact:"Like many German reflexive verbs, the meaning changes with 'sich.' Without it, 'interessieren' means to interest someone else: Das interessiert mich (That interests me)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"leihen", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to lend / to borrow",note:"Irregular: ich leihe, du leihst. Past: geliehen. Not separable (unlike ausleihen).",example:"A: Kannst du mir zehn Euro leihen?\nB: Klar, hier bitte.\nA: Danke! Ich gebe es dir morgen zurück.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you lend me ten euros?\nB: Sure, here you go.\nA: Thanks! I'll give it back tomorrow.",funFact:"Leihen is the base verb. Add prefixes for nuance: ausleihen (borrow from a library), verleihen (to award/bestow), entleihen (formal borrowing)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"komisch", pos:"adj", gender:null,src:"funny / weird",note:"Adjective. Can mean 'funny' (humor) or 'strange' (suspicious). Context decides.",example:"A: Der Film war sehr komisch.\nB: Lustig komisch oder seltsam komisch?\nA: Beides!",exampleSrc:"A: The film was very funny/weird.\nB: Funny-funny or strange-funny?\nA: Both!",funFact:"Komisch comes from Greek 'komikos' (of comedy). In German it drifted to also mean 'strange.' If someone says 'Das ist komisch,' check their face to know which meaning."},
{type:"teach",trg:"sympathisch", pos:"adj", gender:null,src:"likeable / nice (personality)",note:"Adjective. Er ist sehr sympathisch = He is very likeable. Not 'sympathetic' (=mitfühlend)!",example:"A: Wie findest du den neuen Trainer?\nB: Er ist sehr sympathisch!\nA: Ja, er lacht viel.",exampleSrc:"A: What do you think of the new trainer?\nB: He is very likeable!\nA: Yes, he laughs a lot.",funFact:"False friend alert! German 'sympathisch' means likeable, not sympathetic. If you want to say sympathetic, use 'mitfühlend' or 'verständnisvoll.'"}
,
{"type":"fb","s":"Kannst du mir zehn Euro {1}?","a":["leihen"],"opts":["leihen","kaufen","geben","zahlen"],"hint":"Letting someone use your money temporarily.","sSrc":"Can you lend me ten euros?"}]},

{id:"deu_r9l11",title:"Vereinsprüfung",icon:"✅",xp:25,board:true,steps:[
{type:"mc",q:"Ich freue mich, ___ das Konzert heute Abend stattfindet.",opts:["ob","dass","weil","denn"],ans:"dass",hint:"You know for certain it's happening."},
{type:"mc",q:"Er fragt sich, ___ das Training heute ausfällt.",opts:["ob","dass","weil","aber"],ans:"ob",hint:"He's uncertain and wants to find out."},
{type:"fb",s:"Sie {1} sich jeden Samstag im Park zum Joggen.",a:"treffen",opts:["treffen","freuen","ärgern","unterhalten"],hint:"They come together at a location.",sSrc:"They meet up every Saturday in the park for jogging."},
{type:"mc",q:"Wir ___ uns über die Ausstellung im Museum.",opts:["verlieren","unterhalten","vergessen","trainieren (similar)"],ans:"unterhalten",hint:"Think about having a conversation."},
{type:"fb",s:"Er hat Lust, Gitarre zu spielen, {1} er hat kein Instrument.",a:"aber",opts:["aber","dass","ob","denn"],hint:"A contrast between wanting and not having.",sSrc:"He feels like playing guitar, but he has no instrument."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Ich weiß, {1} sie {2} für Kunst interessiert.",blanks:{"1":"dass","2":"sich"},pool:["dass","ob","sich","mich","denn"],hint:"She has interest in art. Which conjunction for a known fact?",sSrc:"I know that she is interested in art."},
{type:"teach",trg:"falls",src:"in case / if",pos:"conj",gender:null,note:"Subordinating conjunction. Verb goes to end.\nSimilar to 'wenn' but implies uncertainty.",example:"A: Falls es regnet, bleiben wir hier.\nB: Gute Idee!",exampleSrc:"A: In case it rains, we stay here.\nB: Good idea!",funFact:"'Falls' implies the condition is less likely than 'wenn.' Use falls when something might or might not happen."},
{type:"mc",q:"___ du dich für den Wettbewerb anmelden möchtest, musst du morgen kommen.",opts:["Ob","Dass (alternative)","Falls","Denn"],ans:"Falls",hint:"This is a conditional: if you want to sign up..."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"sich freuen", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to be happy/excited"},{trg:"sich treffen", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to meet up"},{trg:"sich ärgern", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to be annoyed"},{trg:"sich verlieben", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to fall in love"},{trg:"sich verabreden", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to make plans to meet"}]},
{type:"fb",s:"Hast du {1}, das Heft mitzubringen?",a:"vergessen",opts:["vergessen","verloren","geträumt","organisiert"],hint:"You were supposed to bring it but didn't remember.",sSrc:"Did you forget to bring the notebook?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Sie träumt davon, in einem Zirkus zu arbeiten, ___ sie liebt Tiere.",opts:["dass","denn","ob","sich"],ans:"denn",hint:"This gives the reason. A coordinating conjunction."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Er fragt, {1} wir {2} am Samstag im Theater treffen.",blanks:{"1":"ob","2":"uns"},pool:["ob","dass","uns","sich","euch"],hint:"He's unsure about the plan. Which pronoun for 'wir'?",sSrc:"He asks whether we meet up at the theater on Saturday."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die Veranstaltung {1} nächsten Freitag im Museum statt.",a:"findet",opts:["findet","nimmt","macht","gibt"],hint:"A separable verb meaning 'to take place'.",sSrc:"The event takes place next Friday at the museum."},
{type:"mc",q:"Ich interessiere ___ für Musik und Kultur.",opts:["sich","dich","uns","mich"],ans:"mich",hint:"The reflexive pronoun must match 'ich'."},
{type:"mc",q:"Er sagt, dass er gern Comics ___ und im Internet surft.",opts:["sammeln","gesammelt","sammelt","sammelst"],ans:"sammelt",hint:"After 'dass', the verb goes to the end, conjugated."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Wir nehmen an der Tour teil {1} fotografieren die Vögel im Park, {2} das Wetter ist schön.",blanks:{"1":"und","2":"denn"},pool:["und","aber","denn","dass","ob"],hint:"Two coordinating conjunctions from the ADUSO group: one simply links two actions, and one explains a reason while keeping verb-second order.",sSrc:"We do the tour and photograph the birds in the park, because the weather is nice."},
{type:"fb",s:"Sie ärgert {1} über die Sendung im Radio.",a:"sich",opts:["sich","mich","dich","euch"],hint:"The reflexive pronoun matches 'sie' (she).",sSrc:"She is annoyed about the show on the radio."},
{type:"mc",q:"Weißt du, ___ der Workshop morgen stattfindet ___ am Wochenende?",opts:["dass ... und","ob ... denn","dass ... aber","ob ... oder"],ans:"ob ... oder",hint:"Asking between two possibilities you're unsure about."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"das Konzert", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"the concert"},{trg:"die Zeitschrift", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"the magazine"},{trg:"der Wettbewerb", pos:"noun", gender:"m",src:"the competition"},{trg:"die Bibliothek", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"the library"},{trg:"die Mannschaft", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"the team"}]},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Sie informiert {1}, {2} der Krimi heute Abend im Programm ist.",blanks:{"1":"sich","2":"ob"},pool:["sich","mich","ob","dass","denn"],hint:"She checks for herself whether something is on tonight.",sSrc:"She checks whether the thriller is on tonight."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich weiß, {1} er jeden Tag auf dem Sportplatz trainiert.",a:"dass",opts:["dass","ob","denn","aber"],hint:"You're stating a fact you're certain about.",sSrc:"I know that he trains on the sports field every day."},
{type:"mc",q:"Er bastelt gern, ___ er malt nicht so oft.",opts:["denn","aber","dass","ob"],ans:"aber",hint:"A contrast between two hobbies."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Wir verabreden {1} für die Feier {2} treffen {3} vor dem Zoo.",blanks:{"1":"uns","2":"und","3":"uns"},pool:["uns","sich","und","aber","euch"],hint:"'Wir' reflexive appears twice: making plans AND meeting up.",sSrc:"We arrange to meet for the party and meet up in front of the zoo."},
{type:"mc",q:"Er hat viel Spaß, ___ er aktiv und sportlich ist.",opts:["denn","aber","ob","dass"],ans:"denn",hint:"Gives the reason why he has fun."},
{type:"fb",s:"Sie zeichnet gern Katzen {1} Pferde.",a:"und",opts:["und","aber","dass","ob"],hint:"Connecting two things she likes to draw.",sSrc:"She likes drawing cats and horses."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Ich glaube, {1} sie {2} auf das Fest freut, {3} sie hat schon ein Kleid gekauft.",blanks:{"1":"dass","2":"sich","3":"denn"},pool:["dass","ob","sich","mich","denn","aber"],hint:"A known belief, a reflexive verb, and a reason.",sSrc:"I believe that she is excited about the festival, because she has already bought a dress."}]},

{id:"deu_r9l12",title:"Sport und Beschreibungen",icon:"🏅",xp:10,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Der Mitgliedsausweis",desc:"Verumius pins his Lauftreff membership card to the corkboard. His German life is growing. Time to learn the rest of the Freizeit vocabulary.",goals:["Sports and entertainment vocabulary","Personality adjectives","Everyday verbs for social life"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Tennis", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"tennis",note:"Neuter. Tennis spielen = to play tennis.",example:"A: Spielst du Tennis?\nB: Ja, jeden Samstag im Verein.\nA: Toll! Ich möchte auch anfangen.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you play tennis?\nB: Yes, every Saturday at the club.\nA: Great! I want to start too.",funFact:"Boris Becker won Wimbledon at 17. Germany went tennis-crazy in the 1980s. Every town built courts."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Basketball", pos:"noun", gender:"m",src:"basketball",note:"Masculine. Basketball spielen.",example:"A: Wer spielt heute Basketball?\nB: Die Mannschaft aus Hamburg.\nA: Ich bin Fan!",exampleSrc:"A: Who is playing basketball today?\nB: The team from Hamburg.\nA: I am a fan!",funFact:"Dirk Nowitzki made basketball huge in Germany. The BBL (Basketball Bundesliga) now has 18 teams."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Volleyball", pos:"noun", gender:"m",src:"volleyball",note:"Masculine. Beach-Volleyball is also popular in Germany.",example:"A: Wollen wir Volleyball spielen?\nB: Gern! Am Strand oder in der Halle?",exampleSrc:"A: Do you want to play volleyball?\nB: Sure! At the beach or in the hall?",funFact:"Germany's beach volleyball duo won Olympic gold in 2012 in London. Beach volleyball is huge at German lakes."},
{type:"mc",q:"Which sport uses a net and you hit the ball over it with your hands?",opts:["Basketball","Volleyball","Tennis","Fußball"],ans:"Volleyball",hint:"Teams of six stand on either side of a net."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Rad", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"wheel / bicycle",note:"Neuter. Rad fahren = to cycle. Plural: Räder.",example:"A: Fährst du mit dem Rad zur Arbeit?\nB: Ja, jeden Tag. Es ist gesünder.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you cycle to work?\nB: Yes, every day. It is healthier.",funFact:"Germans cycle about 1,000 km per person per year. Many cities have more bike paths than car lanes."},
{type:"teach",trg:"reiten", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to ride (horse)",note:"Irregular: ich reite, du reitest. Past: geritten (with sein!).",example:"A: Kannst du reiten?\nB: Ein bisschen. Als Kind habe ich geritten.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you ride?\nB: A little. I rode as a child.",funFact:"Germany is one of Europe's top equestrian nations. The German Riding Federation has over 660,000 members."},
{type:"teach",trg:"singen", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to sing",note:"Irregular: ich singe, du singst. Past: gesungen.",example:"A: Singst du gern?\nB: Ja, ich bin im Chor!\nA: Wirklich? Das ist toll!",exampleSrc:"A: Do you like singing?\nB: Yes, I am in a choir!\nA: Really? That is great!",funFact:"Germany has more amateur choirs than any country in Europe. About 3 million Germans sing in a choir."},
{type:"fb",s:"Mia {1} jeden Morgen im Park.",a:["joggt"],opts:["joggt","singt","reitet","malt"],hint:"What does Mia do at the Lauftreff? Running activity.",sSrc:"Mia jogs every morning in the park."},
{type:"teach",trg:"unternehmen", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to undertake / to do (an activity)",note:"Irregular: ich unternehme, du unternimmst. Separable: NOT (inseparable un-).",example:"A: Was wollen wir heute unternehmen?\nB: Wir könnten ins Museum gehen.",exampleSrc:"A: What shall we do today?\nB: We could go to the museum.",funFact:"Despite looking like a separable verb, unternehmen is inseparable. The 'unter' is a prefix, not a particle."},
{type:"teach",trg:"ausgehen", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to go out",note:"Separable: ich gehe aus, du gehst aus. Past: ausgegangen (sein).",example:"A: Gehst du heute Abend aus?\nB: Ja, wir gehen in die Disco.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you going out tonight?\nB: Yes, we are going to the disco.",funFact:"Germans go out later than many Europeans. Dinner at 8, clubs after midnight. Berlin clubs famously open at 1 AM."},
{type:"teach",trg:"probieren", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to try / to taste",note:"Regular: ich probiere, du probierst. Probieren geht über Studieren!",example:"A: Möchtest du den Kuchen probieren?\nB: Ja, gern! Er sieht lecker aus.",exampleSrc:"A: Would you like to try the cake?\nB: Yes, please! It looks delicious.",funFact:"The German proverb 'Probieren geht über Studieren' means 'trying beats studying.' Learning by doing!"},
{type:"mc",q:"'Was wollen wir heute unternehmen?' means:",opts:["What shall we do today?","What are you studying?","Where are you going?","Who is coming along?"],ans:"What shall we do today?",hint:"Planning an activity together. What should we DO?"},
{type:"teach",trg:"tauschen", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to swap / to exchange",note:"Regular: ich tausche. Tauschbörse = swap market.",example:"A: Wollen wir die Plätze tauschen?\nB: Ja, klar! Ich sitze gern am Fenster.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you want to swap seats?\nB: Yes, sure! I like sitting by the window.",funFact:"Germany has a strong Tauschkultur. Swap parties for clothes, books, and toys are common, especially in Berlin."},
{type:"teach",trg:"teilen", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to share / to divide",note:"Regular: ich teile. Teilen ist leben! (Sharing is living.)",example:"A: Sollen wir die Pizza teilen?\nB: Gute Idee! Eine ganze Pizza ist zu viel.",exampleSrc:"A: Should we share the pizza?\nB: Good idea! A whole pizza is too much.",funFact:"In German restaurants, 'getrennt' means separate bills and 'zusammen' means one bill. Germans often split."},
{type:"teach",trg:"schimpfen", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to scold / to complain",note:"Regular: ich schimpfe. Schimpfwort = swear word.",example:"A: Warum schimpft Hildi?\nB: Weil jemand den Müll falsch sortiert hat!",exampleSrc:"A: Why is Hildi scolding?\nB: Because someone sorted the trash wrong!",funFact:"Germans are known for Beschwerdekultur (complaint culture). If the rules are broken, someone WILL say something."},
{type:"fb",s:"Sollen wir die Rechnung {1}?",a:["teilen"],opts:["teilen","tauschen","schimpfen","probieren"],hint:"To split the bill between two people.",sSrc:"Should we split the bill?"}
]},

// ─── Lesson: Beschreibungen ───
{id:"deu_r9l13",title:"Beschreibungen",icon:"⭐",xp:10,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Beschreibungen",desc:"From fantastic to boring, from famous to special: learn the adjectives that bring German conversations to life. Describe people, events, and experiences with precision.",goals:["Learn ten essential German adjectives","Describe people, events, and experiences","Use adjectives in context with nouns and verbs"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"fantastisch", pos:"adj", gender:null,src:"fantastic",note:"Same in English! Easily recognizable.",example:"A: Wie war das Konzert?\nB: Fantastisch! Die Band war super.",exampleSrc:"A: How was the concert?\nB: Fantastic! The band was great.",funFact:"Many German adjectives for positive emotions are borrowed from French or Latin: fantastisch, romantisch, sympathisch."},
{type:"teach",trg:"langweilig", pos:"adj", gender:null,src:"boring",note:"Lang (long) + weilig (time-related). Literally: making time feel long.",example:"A: Wie findest du den Film?\nB: Langweilig. Lass uns gehen.",exampleSrc:"A: How do you find the movie?\nB: Boring. Let us leave.",funFact:"The word structure tells you the meaning: lang (long) + Weile (while). Something that makes time stretch."},
{type:"teach",trg:"nett", pos:"adj", gender:null,src:"nice / kind",note:"Common everyday compliment. 'Das ist nett von dir.'",example:"A: Dein Nachbar ist sehr nett.\nB: Ja, er hilft mir oft mit dem Müll.",exampleSrc:"A: Your neighbor is very nice.\nB: Yes, he often helps me with the trash.",funFact:"In German culture, 'nett' can also be faint praise. 'Nett ist die kleine Schwester von...' means nett is the lesser version of truly good."},
{type:"teach",trg:"toll", pos:"adj", gender:null,src:"great / awesome",note:"Very common positive adjective. Informal but widely used.",example:"A: Ich habe den Job bekommen!\nB: Toll! Herzlichen Glückwunsch!",exampleSrc:"A: I got the job!\nB: Great! Congratulations!",funFact:"'Toll' originally meant 'crazy/mad' in Old German. Over centuries it shifted to mean 'amazing.' Similar to English 'terrific.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"witzig", pos:"adj", gender:null,src:"witty / funny",note:"From Witz (joke). Ein witziger Mensch = a funny person.",example:"A: Der Film war sehr witzig.\nB: Ja, ich habe so viel gelacht!",exampleSrc:"A: The movie was very funny.\nB: Yes, I laughed so much!",funFact:"German humor exists! Loriot, a legendary German comedian, proved that dry observational humor is universal."},
{type:"mc",q:"The opposite of 'langweilig' (boring) would be:",opts:["freundlich und nett","toll","spannend","witzig"],ans:"spannend",hint:"Something that keeps you on the edge of your seat. Exciting."},
{type:"teach",trg:"spannend", pos:"adj", gender:null,src:"exciting / thrilling",note:"From spannen (to stretch/tighten). Like a taut bowstring.",example:"A: Das Buch ist sehr spannend!\nB: Wirklich? Worum geht es?",exampleSrc:"A: The book is very exciting!\nB: Really? What is it about?",funFact:"Spannend comes from the same root as English 'suspense.' A Spannungsroman is a thriller novel."},
{type:"teach",trg:"beliebt", pos:"adj", gender:null,src:"popular / well-liked",note:"From belieben (to please). Ein beliebtes Restaurant.",example:"A: Diese Sendung ist sehr beliebt.\nB: Ja, alle schauen sie!",exampleSrc:"A: This show is very popular.\nB: Yes, everyone watches it!",funFact:"Beliebt is a participial adjective. 'Es beliebt mir' (it pleases me) is the archaic origin."},
{type:"teach",trg:"berühmt", pos:"adj", gender:null,src:"famous",note:"From Ruhm (fame). Ein berühmter Musiker.",example:"A: Kennst du diesen berühmten Musiker?\nB: Ja, er ist überall bekannt!",exampleSrc:"A: Do you know this famous musician?\nB: Yes, he is known everywhere!",funFact:"Be-rühm-t: the prefix be- + Ruhm (glory) + -t ending. 'Touched by glory.' German word building at its finest."},
{type:"teach",trg:"besonders", pos:"adv", gender:null,src:"especially / particularly",note:"Adverb. Besonders gut = especially good.",example:"A: Was gefällt dir an Berlin?\nB: Besonders die Kultur und die Musik.",exampleSrc:"A: What do you like about Berlin?\nB: Especially the culture and the music.",funFact:"Besonders comes from 'besonder' (special/separate). Something that stands apart from the rest."},
{type:"teach",trg:"meistens", pos:"adv", gender:null,src:"mostly / usually",note:"Adverb. Meistens + verb = what you usually do.",example:"A: Was machst du am Wochenende?\nB: Meistens gehe ich spazieren.",exampleSrc:"A: What do you do on weekends?\nB: I usually go for a walk.",funFact:"Meistens comes from 'meist' (most). The -ens ending turns it into 'for the most part.'"},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Der Film war {1} und {2}. Ich habe so viel gelacht!",blanks:{"1":"witzig","2":"toll"},pool:["witzig","toll","langweilig","schlimm","nett","traurig"],hint:"A funny and great movie. Two positive adjectives.",sSrc:"The film was funny and great. I laughed so much!"},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"fantastisch", pos:"adj", gender:null,src:"fantastic"},{trg:"langweilig", pos:"adj", gender:null,src:"boring"},{trg:"spannend", pos:"adj", gender:null,src:"exciting"},{trg:"beliebt", pos:"adj", gender:null,src:"popular"},{trg:"berühmt", pos:"adj", gender:null,src:"famous"},{trg:"witzig", pos:"adj", gender:null,src:"funny"},{trg:"nett", pos:"adj", gender:null,src:"nice"},{trg:"toll", pos:"adj", gender:null,src:"great"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"'Reiten' ist ein Hobby. Was macht man dabei?",opts:["Man fährt Fahrrad","Man reitet ein Pferd","Man singt zusammen Lieder","Man spielt Tennis"],ans:"Man reitet ein Pferd",hint:"This hobby involves an animal. 'Reiten' means to ride, but not a bicycle."},
{type:"mc",q:"Which adjective describes something that is famous and known to many people?",opts:["nett","meistens","beliebt","berühmt"],ans:"berühmt",hint:"This word comes from 'Ruhm' meaning fame or glory."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die neue Sendung ist sehr {1} in Deutschland.",a:["beliebt"],opts:["beliebt","berühmt","besonders","meistens"],hint:"Many people like it and watch it. Not that it is internationally famous, but widely liked.",sSrc:"The new show is very popular in Germany."},
{type:"fb",s:"Das Konzert war {1}! Alle haben getanzt.",a:["fantastisch"],opts:["fantastisch","langweilig","schlimm","traurig"],hint:"The concert was amazing. Everyone danced. Which positive adjective fits?",sSrc:"The concert was fantastic! Everyone danced."}
]},

// ─── L9: Unterhaltung und Events ───
{id:"deu_r9l14",title:"Unterhaltung und Events",icon:"🎶",xp:10,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Unterhaltung und Events",desc:"From bands to festivals, clubs to quizzes: entertainment vocabulary for your social life in Germany. Plus useful verbs for making plans and exchanging ideas.",goals:["Learn entertainment and event vocabulary","Use verbs for planning: vereinbaren, austauschen","Describe events with new adjectives"]},
{type:"mc",q:"What is Lukas proposing in the group chat?",opts:["A running competition","A train trip to Munich","A museum visit","A concert in Berlin"],ans:"A train trip to Munich",hint:"He found cheap ICE tickets. Where does he want to go?"},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Band", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"the band (music group)",note:"Feminine. Plural: die Bands. Borrowed from English.",example:"A: Welche Band spielte auf dem Festival?\nB: Eine Indie-Band aus Berlin.\nA: Waren sie gut?",exampleSrc:"A: Which band played at the festival?\nB: An indie band from Berlin.\nA: Were they good?",funFact:"Germany has a huge live music scene. Rock am Ring, Wacken Open Air, and Splash! are among Europe's biggest festivals."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Disco", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"the disco / nightclub",note:"Feminine. Also: die Disko. Plural: die Discos.",example:"A: Gehen wir heute Abend in die Disco?\nB: Ja, die Musik dort ist super!\nA: Um wie viel Uhr?",exampleSrc:"A: Shall we go to the club tonight?\nB: Yes, the music there is great!\nA: What time?",funFact:"Germans still say 'Disco' for nightclub, though younger people also say 'Club.' Berlin is considered the techno capital of the world."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Festival", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"the festival",note:"Neuter. Plural: die Festivals. From English.",example:"A: Warst du schon auf einem Festival?\nB: Ja, letztes Jahr auf dem Wacken Open Air.\nA: Drei Tage Musik und Camping!",exampleSrc:"A: Have you been to a festival?\nB: Yes, last year at Wacken Open Air.\nA: Three days of music and camping!",funFact:"Wacken Open Air is the world's largest heavy metal festival, held in a tiny village with just 2,000 residents but 85,000 visitors."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Klub", pos:"noun", gender:"m",src:"the club",note:"Masculine. Plural: die Klubs. Also spelled Club.",example:"A: Bist du Mitglied in einem Klub?\nB: Ja, in einem Leseclub.\nA: Was lest ihr gerade?",exampleSrc:"A: Are you a member of a club?\nB: Yes, in a book club.\nA: What are you reading now?",funFact:"The Berghain in Berlin is often called the world's most exclusive nightclub. The doormen decide who enters based on criteria nobody fully understands."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Plakat", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"the poster (public)",note:"Neuter. Plural: die Plakate. For advertising posters, event announcements.",example:"A: Hast du das Plakat für das Konzert gesehen?\nB: Ja, es hängt am Bahnhof.\nA: Die Farben sind toll!",exampleSrc:"A: Have you seen the poster for the concert?\nB: Yes, it hangs at the train station.\nA: The colors are great!",funFact:"Germany has Litfaßsäulen (advertising columns) on streets since 1855, invented by Ernst Litfaß to reduce wild poster chaos."},
{type:"mc",q:"Die Band spielt heute Abend in einem Klub. Was ist ein 'Klub'?",opts:["A school","A club or venue","A kitchen","A full hospital ward"],ans:"A club or venue",hint:"English and German share this word for a social gathering place."},
{type:"fb",s:"Hast du das {1} für das Festival gesehen? Es hängt an der Wand.",a:["Plakat"],opts:["Plakat","Poster","Quiz","Rätsel"],hint:"Which noun means a large printed announcement for public display?",sSrc:"Did you see the poster for the festival? It hangs on the wall."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Poster", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"the poster (decorative)",note:"Neuter. Plural: die Poster. Borrowed from English. More personal than Plakat.",example:"A: Ich habe ein neues Poster für mein Zimmer.\nB: Was ist darauf?\nA: Ein Foto von den Alpen.",exampleSrc:"A: I have a new poster for my room.\nB: What's on it?\nA: A photo of the Alps.",funFact:"Plakat is for public/commercial posters. Poster is for decorative ones at home. Germans keep both words with different meanings."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Quiz", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"the quiz",note:"Neuter. Plural: die Quiz or Quizze. Borrowed from English.",example:"A: Machen wir ein Quiz über Deutschland?\nB: Gute Idee! Wer weiß mehr?\nA: Ich bin bereit!",exampleSrc:"A: Shall we do a quiz about Germany?\nB: Good idea! Who knows more?\nA: I'm ready!",funFact:"'Wer wird Millionär?' (Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?) has been running since 1999 with host Günther Jauch."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Rätsel", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"the puzzle / riddle",note:"Neuter. Plural: die Rätsel. Ein Kreuzworträtsel = crossword puzzle.",example:"A: Ich liebe Rätsel!\nB: Dann mach das Kreuzworträtsel in der Zeitung.\nA: Gute Idee!",exampleSrc:"A: I love puzzles!\nB: Then do the crossword in the newspaper.\nA: Good idea!",funFact:"The Brothers Grimm filled their fairy tales with riddles. Rumpelstiltskin is basically one giant name-guessing puzzle."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Team", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"the team",note:"Neuter. Plural: die Teams. Synonym: die Mannschaft (more traditional).",example:"A: Unser Team hat gewonnen!\nB: Fantastisch! Wie war das Spiel?\nA: Drei zu eins!",exampleSrc:"A: Our team won!\nB: Fantastic! How was the game?\nA: Three to one!",funFact:"Germans use both 'Team' (modern, borrowed) and 'Mannschaft' (traditional). In business, Team is preferred. In football, Mannschaft rules."},
{type:"mc",q:"Kannst du das Rätsel lösen? Es hat zehn Fragen. Was ist ein 'Rätsel'?",opts:["A recipe","A riddle or puzzle","A radio show","A concert"],ans:"A riddle or puzzle",hint:"Think of something that challenges your brain to find answers."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wir machen ein {1}. Wer die meisten Fragen richtig beantwortet, gewinnt.",a:["Quiz"],opts:["Quiz","Rätsel","Poster","Plakat"],hint:"Which English loanword describes a competition with questions?",sSrc:"We are doing a quiz. Whoever answers the most questions correctly wins."},
{type:"teach",trg:"vereinbaren", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to arrange / to agree upon",note:"Inseparable: ich vereinbare. Perfekt: hat vereinbart.",example:"A: Wollen wir einen Termin vereinbaren?\nB: Ja, passt dir Dienstag?\nA: Perfekt, Dienstag um zehn.",exampleSrc:"A: Shall we arrange an appointment?\nB: Yes, does Tuesday work for you?\nA: Perfect, Tuesday at ten.",funFact:"From Verein (club). Vereinbaren means to come to an agreement. Very German: even scheduling is an act of unification."},
{type:"teach",trg:"auspacken", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to unpack",note:"Separable: ich packe aus. Opposite of einpacken.",example:"A: Hast du den Koffer schon ausgepackt?\nB: Nein, ich bin zu müde.\nA: Das mache ich morgen.",exampleSrc:"A: Have you unpacked the suitcase yet?\nB: No, I'm too tired.\nA: I'll do it tomorrow.",funFact:"In colloquial German, 'auspacken' also means to reveal secrets. A witness who 'auspackt' is spilling everything."},
{type:"teach",trg:"austauschen", pos:"verb", gender:null,src:"to exchange / to swap",note:"Separable: ich tausche aus. Emphasizes mutual exchange.",example:"A: Wollen wir Telefonnummern austauschen?\nB: Ja, gerne! Hier ist meine.\nA: Danke! Ich schreibe dir.",exampleSrc:"A: Shall we exchange phone numbers?\nB: Yes, gladly! Here is mine.\nA: Thanks! I'll text you.",funFact:"Schüleraustausch (student exchange) is very popular. About 20,000 German students go abroad each year."},
{type:"teach",trg:"romantisch", pos:"adj", gender:null,src:"romantic",note:"Adjective. Same root as English. Ein romantischer Abend.",example:"A: Der Film war sehr romantisch.\nB: Ja, aber auch ein bisschen kitschig.\nA: Das ist doch das Beste daran!",exampleSrc:"A: The film was very romantic.\nB: Yes, but also a bit cheesy.\nA: That's the best part!",funFact:"The Rhine Valley inspired the German Romantic movement in the 19th century. Romantisch comes from this era."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"die Band", pos:"noun", gender:"f",src:"the band"},{trg:"das Festival", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"the festival"},{trg:"der Klub", pos:"noun", gender:"m",src:"the club"},{trg:"das Rätsel", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"the puzzle"},{trg:"das Team", pos:"noun", gender:"n",src:"the team"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"Wo kann man in Berlin am besten tanzen gehen?",opts:["In die Disco","In das Festival","In das Rätsel","In die Band"],ans:"In die Disco",hint:"A place you go to at night to dance to music. Not an outdoor event."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wollen wir einen Termin {1}?",a:["vereinbaren"],opts:["vereinbaren","auspacken","austauschen","probieren"],hint:"To arrange or agree upon a meeting time. Related to 'Verein' (club).",sSrc:"Shall we arrange an appointment?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'auspacken' umgangssprachlich?",opts:["Geheimnisse verraten","Einen Koffer packen","Ein Geschenk kaufen","Einen Brief schreiben"],ans:"Geheimnisse verraten",hint:"Beyond its literal meaning of unpacking, this verb has a colloquial meaning about revealing information."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wollen wir Telefonnummern {1}?",a:["austauschen"],opts:["austauschen","auspacken","vereinbaren","tauschen"],hint:"To mutually exchange something. The 'aus-' prefix emphasizes the two-way nature.",sSrc:"Shall we exchange phone numbers?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Welches Wort beschreibt einen Abend bei Kerzenlicht?",opts:["romantisch","langweilig","witzig","spannend"],ans:"romantisch",hint:"Candles, soft music, a special dinner. Which adjective captures this atmosphere?"}
]}
]};

export default UNIT_9;
